00:00:23.377 --> 00:00:25.210
PROFESSOR: OK, so let
me just quickly remind

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:28.120
you of what we've done
what we did last time.

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:31.931
So unfortunately, today is going
to be a little bit of what I

00:00:31.931 --> 00:00:34.430
wanted to do this time and a
little bit of what I would have

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:36.050
wanted to have been done
in recitation yesterday,

00:00:36.050 --> 00:00:37.980
because all recitations
were cancelled.

00:00:37.980 --> 00:00:41.900
So today is going to include
a few steps along the way

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:44.010
that I skipped over last time.

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:46.157
OK, so to review
from last time, we

00:00:46.157 --> 00:00:47.490
talked about central potentials.

00:00:47.490 --> 00:00:50.110
The energy operator had a radial
derivative term, an angular

00:00:50.110 --> 00:00:51.822
momentum term, and
a potential term.

00:00:51.822 --> 00:00:54.280
So this would be true regardless
of whether we were central

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:54.880
or not.

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:57.004
But if we have a central
potential, where this only

00:00:57.004 --> 00:00:59.890
depends on the magnitude
of the radius vector,

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:01.970
then we can use
separation of variables,

00:01:01.970 --> 00:01:05.560
and write an energy eigenstate
as a radial part-- which

00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:09.300
we will sneakily pull out a
factor of 1 over the radius--

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.350
as we saw last time, that
was particularly convenient.

00:01:12.350 --> 00:01:15.870
It took care of this r and made
everything nice and simple.

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:19.102
So a radial part times
a spherical harmonic.

00:01:19.102 --> 00:01:20.810
The reason we use a
spherical harmonic is

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:23.940
that neither of these two
terms depend on the angular

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:24.610
coordinates.

00:01:24.610 --> 00:01:27.240
The angular momentum, we know
what its eigenfunctions are,

00:01:27.240 --> 00:01:28.656
so if we use a
spherical harmonic,

00:01:28.656 --> 00:01:32.060
this angular momentum
becomes just a constant.

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:34.320
And having separated
in this form,

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:37.110
and pulling out that
sneaky factor of 1 over r,

00:01:37.110 --> 00:01:41.100
the energy eigenvalue equation
reduces to a simple 1-D

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:44.560
effective energy
eigenvalue equation

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:49.060
with a simple dr squared,
and an effective potential,

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:53.490
where the effective potential is
the original central potential

00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:55.320
plus an angular
momentum term, often

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:59.870
referred to the angular
momentum barrier-- which

00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:03.400
is proportional
to-- as Matt says,

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:06.800
as Professor Evans
says, in 804, one

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:09.680
is forced to say h bar
squared upon 2m repeatedly.

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:12.180
And he pointed out that it would
be much more efficient if I

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:14.620
would just come up with a
simple variable for saying it

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:15.750
or sound.

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:19.188
So I will attempt to
henceforth call it pfft.

00:02:19.188 --> 00:02:20.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:23.000
So the effective
potential is pfft,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.410
l, l plus 1 upon r squared
plus the central part

00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:29.870
of the potential-- props
to Professor Evans.

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:32.160
And this is true in general
for central potential.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:35.330
The last thing we notice of
this is that since the energy

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:37.920
eigenvalue equation has been
reduced to this form, which

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:40.120
depends on l, but is
independent of m-- m

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:43.020
appears nowhere here--
the energy can't possibly

00:02:43.020 --> 00:02:52.360
depend on m, although
it can depend on l.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:53.500
It's just e of l.

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:55.420
And thus, for every
different value of m,

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:59.410
I will get the same energy--
fixed l, different m.

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:03.390
And there are how many
values of m for a fixed l?

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:04.110
2l plus 1.

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:15.110
So the degeneracy
of El is 2l plus 1.

00:03:15.110 --> 00:03:15.610
Right?

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:17.290
That's general for
any central potential.

00:03:17.290 --> 00:03:18.790
It only requires
spherical symmetry.

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:26.020
So then we say the example of
the cooling potential, where

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:27.920
the potential is minus
E squared upon r.

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:33.465
And we solved-- or I quickly
reviewed the solution

00:03:33.465 --> 00:03:39.710
of the energy
eigenvalue equation.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:42.870
I'll write it that
way-- where r of what

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:46.440
I will call-- in place of
E I, will simply write n.

00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:56.240
Rnl is equal to e to
the minus r over 2

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:09.300
r naught n times r over r
naught to the l plus 1 times

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:18.200
some simple function v sub
n of l of r over r naught,

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:24.920
with the energy nlm
being equal to E naught--

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:27.730
or I should say e Rydberg in
our notation of last time--

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:30.750
upon n squared
minus bound state.

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:33.100
So let's talk
about this quickly.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:37.560
This term-- the fact that it
goes exponentially-- falls

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:39.850
exponentially at
large distances--

00:04:39.850 --> 00:04:46.359
came from the asymptotic
analysis at r goes to infinity.

00:04:46.359 --> 00:04:48.150
And this is just saying
it's a bound state.

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:50.410
The probability density
falls off exponentially

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:53.050
as we get to large radius.

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:59.470
This term came from
the asymptotic analysis

00:04:59.470 --> 00:05:01.180
near r goes to zero.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:03.620
And near r goes to
zero, the only term

00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:07.850
that matters is in the
effective-- this is one upon r.

00:05:07.850 --> 00:05:10.920
This is 1 over r squared, so
this gets large more rapidly.

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:13.110
This term is important,
and that l, l plus 1

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.660
gave us r to the l plus 1.

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:18.080
We work in dimensionless
variables, rho.

00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:20.270
And here, I replace rho
with r over r naught,

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:22.061
where r naught was the
characteristic scale

00:05:22.061 --> 00:05:23.640
we computed last time.

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:26.650
And finally, this
function V sub nl

00:05:26.650 --> 00:05:31.710
satisfied-- it again satisfied
the energy eigenvalue equation,

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:33.500
but having pulled
out these factors

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.130
such that asymptotically,
its regular.

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.820
So this function
must be regular,

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.890
smooth-- no
divergences, no poles--

00:05:41.890 --> 00:05:46.610
as r goes to infinity and to 0.

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:47.250
OK.

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:50.380
And then we solved this
by series expansion.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:52.340
And from termination of
the series expansion,

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:54.310
we got that the energy--
we got a relationship

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:56.100
between the energy
and l and n, and

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:58.240
in particular the
relationship-- this

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:04.000
came from termination
of the series, just

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.985
like it did for the
harmonic oscillator.

00:06:08.870 --> 00:06:10.300
And the termination
series gave us

00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:12.721
that the energy was equal
to minus a constant over n

00:06:12.721 --> 00:06:13.220
squared.

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:19.580
With one additional
condition, which

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:22.800
is that n had to
be greater than l.

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.849
n had to be an integer
greater than l.

00:06:24.849 --> 00:06:27.140
And l, of course, has to be
greater than or equal to 0.

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:35.250
So let me just
quickly tell you how

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:38.840
this arises, because this is an
important fact about hydrogen

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:41.860
which I want you to understand.

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:45.430
So the way that arises is we
got the energy from a series

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:50.096
expansion for this remaining
function of rv and l of r.

00:06:50.096 --> 00:06:51.900
And that series
expansion started out

00:06:51.900 --> 00:07:00.020
by saying let v be of the
form sum over j of a sub j, r

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:05.235
over r naught, the dimensionless
variable rho, to the j,

00:07:05.235 --> 00:07:07.660
to the j-th power, so
it's a power series.

00:07:07.660 --> 00:07:09.890
And when we plug this
whole form, together

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:12.660
with this series expansion,
into that differential equation,

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:16.460
we get-- just like we did before
for a harmonic oscillator--

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:18.870
we get a set of
relations between

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:21.120
the various coefficients
in that series.

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:24.240
And we solve that by
saying a sub j plus 1--

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:26.530
by deriving a recursion
relation-- is equal to a sub

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:34.350
j times 2, square
root of epsilon times

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:53.930
j plus l plus 1 minus 1 upon
j plus 1, j plus 2l plus 2.

00:07:58.210 --> 00:07:58.860
OK, fine.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:00.151
We get this recursion relation.

00:08:00.151 --> 00:08:02.410
It looks absolutely
awful, but it tells you

00:08:02.410 --> 00:08:07.010
that if you know a0, say, is
a constant which is not 0--

00:08:07.010 --> 00:08:08.635
if it's zero, then
they're all 0-- then

00:08:08.635 --> 00:08:11.170
this function is identically
0, because a j plus 1

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:12.940
is a j times some constant.

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:15.321
So this had better
not vanish-- a sub 0.

00:08:15.321 --> 00:08:16.820
So the first term,
the constant term

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.774
doesn't vanish, which is good.

00:08:18.774 --> 00:08:20.690
It tells us V doesn't
vanish, so we've already

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:21.439
learned something.

00:08:21.439 --> 00:08:25.250
If V doesn't vanish
identically at the origin,

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:29.085
then we can determine a1 from
a0 by multiplying by this.

00:08:29.085 --> 00:08:32.030
j is 0 in this, and
l is whatever number

00:08:32.030 --> 00:08:33.919
we fix from ylm.

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:34.460
And so on.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:35.799
We can deduce all
the higher a sub l's.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:37.000
It's a series expansion.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.260
This is the recursion
relation for it.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:44.920
However, note the following
thing-- as j gets large,

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:49.690
so we go to higher and
higher orders in the series,

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:53.100
then j is much larger than
whatever fixed number l is,

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:55.410
and much larger than
whatever fixed number 2 is.

00:08:55.410 --> 00:09:01.610
So this asymptotes to aj times
roughly 2 epsilon j upon j

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:03.410
plus 1 j.

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:06.915
At very large j, this just
goes to 2 epsilon over j.

00:09:06.915 --> 00:09:08.540
Now, let's think
about what that means.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:11.530
If I have that aj plus
1 is roughly equal

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:18.720
to aj times root epsilon
times 2 over j plus 1,

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:24.900
I guess, then this tells me
that every time I increase j,

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:28.120
I get a factor of j plus 1
and another factor of 2 root

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:28.810
epsilon.

00:09:28.810 --> 00:09:33.450
This tells me that a sub j
is equal to a sub 0 times

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:40.174
2 root epsilon to the
j over j factorial.

00:09:40.174 --> 00:09:41.840
But those are the
expansion coefficients

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:48.230
of an exponential-- quantity
to the n over n factorial.

00:09:48.230 --> 00:09:51.080
But that's bad, because
if this series is

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:55.220
the exponential series with
argument 2 root epsilon,

00:09:55.220 --> 00:10:03.840
then this series becomes E to
the 2 root epsilon r over r0.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:08.090
But that's bad, because that
would exactly swamp this term.

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:09.810
That would defeat the
asymptotic analysis

00:10:09.810 --> 00:10:10.810
we did at the beginning.

00:10:10.810 --> 00:10:13.980
If this term, V, is
growing so large twice

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:17.310
as rapidly as this
is going to 0,

00:10:17.310 --> 00:10:19.470
then the net is
diverging at infinity.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:20.820
That's bad.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:23.790
So in order for this--
for the series expansion--

00:10:23.790 --> 00:10:27.330
to describe a good function that
really does vanish at infinity,

00:10:27.330 --> 00:10:30.150
we need that this
doesn't happen.

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:31.750
So it must be true
that j doesn't

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:35.350
get large enough that
the exponential in V

00:10:35.350 --> 00:10:37.800
overwhelms the
decaying exponential

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:39.240
from the asymptotic analysis.

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:40.450
Everyone cool with that?

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:42.044
So it has to terminate.

00:10:42.044 --> 00:10:44.460
But if it terminates-- let's
look at the coefficient here.

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:51.210
If it terminates, this says that
2 root epsilon times j plus--

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:53.810
and if it terminates, that says
that there's some j maximum.

00:10:56.437 --> 00:10:57.770
Well, let me write it over here.

00:10:57.770 --> 00:10:59.270
If it terminates,
that means there's

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:02.850
some value j such
that aj plus 1 is 0.

00:11:02.850 --> 00:11:05.830
But if aj plus 1 is zero,
how can that possibly be?

00:11:05.830 --> 00:11:08.180
It must be that for
that maximum value of j,

00:11:08.180 --> 00:11:10.850
the numerator
vanishes-- specifically

00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:12.900
for that maximum value of j.

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:13.700
Yeah?

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:15.690
Well, what's the condition
for that numerator

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:17.390
to vanish for a
specific value of j?

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:21.360
I'll j sub m, or j
max, the maximum value,

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:25.470
such that a sub j
max plus 1 vanishes.

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:30.080
So j plus l plus 1
must be equal to 1.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.300
Or said differently,
epsilon-- which

00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:37.060
is the energy in units
of e0, must be equal to 1

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:45.080
over 4 g max plus l plus
1, quantity squared.

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:46.510
Cool?

00:11:46.510 --> 00:11:50.070
So that means that our
solutions, or states psi,

00:11:50.070 --> 00:11:52.700
are now labeled
by three integers.

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:56.440
they're labeled by l And by
m from spherical harmonics,

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:58.440
but they're also labeled
by the value j max.

00:12:02.710 --> 00:12:07.452
And j max can be any number
from 0 to infinity, right?

00:12:07.452 --> 00:12:08.910
Strictly, it
shouldn't be infinite,

00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:12.930
but any finite number, any
countable, any integer--

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:16.570
because eventually the
series terminates at j max.

00:12:16.570 --> 00:12:18.230
So it's labeled by
these three numbers,

00:12:18.230 --> 00:12:28.680
and the energy of lmj max
is equal to e0 minus over 4.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:32.520
And this e0 over 4 we already
saw was e Rydberg, 13.6 dv,

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:33.680
times what value?

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:39.722
Well, here's the energy in
units of e0-- jm plus l plus 1,

00:12:39.722 --> 00:12:40.430
quantity squared.

00:12:43.890 --> 00:12:46.650
Where L is greater
than or equal to 0,

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:51.090
j sub m is greater than
or equal to 0, and 1 is 1.

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:52.990
But this is sort of cumbersome.

00:12:52.990 --> 00:12:56.620
We can just as well
call this quantity n,

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:59.370
where n is greater
than l as an integer.

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:01.210
It can't be equal
to l, but it could

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:03.900
be 1 greater than l,
or any greater integer.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:04.930
Is that cool?

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:07.420
So instead of labeling
it by jm, the point

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:11.370
at which the series terminates,
we'll label it by n,

00:13:11.370 --> 00:13:15.230
and you can deduce what jm is
by subtracting I plus 1 from n.

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:17.200
That tells you where
the series terminates.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.510
Notice that this tells
you something nice.

00:13:19.510 --> 00:13:25.640
This power series for V,
if n is equal to l plus 1,

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:26.850
has how many terms in it?

00:13:29.389 --> 00:13:31.430
So say it out loud, just
think about it a second.

00:13:31.430 --> 00:13:35.834
If n is equal to l
plus 1, how many terms

00:13:35.834 --> 00:13:37.750
are there, that are
non-vanishing in the power

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:38.250
series?

00:13:40.874 --> 00:13:42.540
I won't call on you,
but raise your hand

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:43.540
when you have an answer.

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:55.480
What's the value of j max
if n is equal to l plus 1?

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:58.060
So what term is the first
one to vanish in the series?

00:14:01.254 --> 00:14:02.920
OK, so how many terms
are non-vanishing?

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:07.560
Yeah, just the one--
just the first term.

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:11.320
So when l is as large
as it can possibly

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:18.480
be-- when l is equal to n minus
1, V is a constant function.

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:20.451
It's just constant.

00:14:20.451 --> 00:14:27.340
When l is one less, when l is
n minus 1, or n is l plus 2,

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:31.559
then V has two terms in it--
a constant, and a linear.

00:14:31.559 --> 00:14:33.475
So the greater the
difference between l and n,

00:14:33.475 --> 00:14:37.140
the more terms there
are in the series.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:39.380
OK?

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:44.360
So anyway, this leads to
this form of the energy.

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:48.720
But as is usually the case, this
sort of a brute force analysis

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:50.570
doesn't give us a
whole lot of insight

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:53.770
into why we get the
qualitative features we do.

00:14:53.770 --> 00:14:55.990
In particular, the
qualitative feature

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:58.870
that stands out most obviously
to me-- I don't know about you

00:14:58.870 --> 00:15:02.830
guys-- is the fact that
the degeneracy is now much,

00:15:02.830 --> 00:15:03.980
much larger.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:07.200
In particular, we know
from basic principles

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:09.220
of a central potential--
as we just reviewed--

00:15:09.220 --> 00:15:12.980
that anytime a potential
is symmetrically invariant,

00:15:12.980 --> 00:15:16.930
is spherically
symmetric-- any time

00:15:16.930 --> 00:15:20.390
the potential is spherically
symmetric, rotationally

00:15:20.390 --> 00:15:22.720
invariant-- then there
must be degeneracy

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:26.400
of 2l plus 1 for every energy
eigenstate-- there must be.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:29.420
The l could be zero, but if
there's any angular momentum,

00:15:29.420 --> 00:15:31.750
then that degeneracy
must be 2l plus 1.

00:15:31.750 --> 00:15:33.315
But this is much
more degenerate.

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.480
And in fact, how
degenerate is it?

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:45.430
Well, for any given
En, the degeneracy

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:50.210
is equal to-- well, what are
the possible values of l?

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:54.390
So we have some state for
every different value of l.

00:15:54.390 --> 00:15:58.580
l could be equal to 0, and it
can go up to n minus 1, right?

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:07.290
Because, again,
n is some integer

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:09.640
which could vanish, l plus 1.

00:16:09.640 --> 00:16:12.360
So as small as this can be is 0.

00:16:12.360 --> 00:16:14.520
So n can be l plus 1,
or anything greater.

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:20.300
I.e.: l can go up to n minus
1, but it can't be any greater.

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:24.806
Then for every value of
l, there is a state n--

00:16:24.806 --> 00:16:27.222
there's a value of n which
could be minus l all the way up

00:16:27.222 --> 00:16:28.202
to l in integer steps.

00:16:28.202 --> 00:16:29.410
So how many states are there?

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:32.830
Well there's one state for
every value of n, l, and m.

00:16:32.830 --> 00:16:34.490
So it's this sum.

00:16:34.490 --> 00:16:37.140
The sum on m for minus
l to l is 2l plus 1.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:43.240
So this is the sum n minus
1, l equals 0, of 2l plus 1.

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:45.600
And this is equal to,
kind of beautifully, n

00:16:45.600 --> 00:16:52.150
squared-- just
arithmetic series.

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:57.440
So we have this huge
degeneracy, which

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:00.340
is much larger than 2l plus 1.

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:03.910
It's the sum over 2l plus
1 from l to 0 to n minus 1.

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:05.615
Where is this
degeneracy coming from?

00:17:05.615 --> 00:17:06.115
Why?

00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:16.160
So quantum mechanically,
we know the following--

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:17.880
we've learned the
following-- and I

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:20.940
hope it's under your
fingernails at this point--

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:22.890
that when you see
a degeneracy, you

00:17:22.890 --> 00:17:26.619
should expect that degeneracy
to follow from some symmetry.

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:28.980
There's some symmetry
of the system that

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:31.160
is leading to a degeneracy
by virtue of the fact

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:33.285
that the generators of that
symmetry-- for example,

00:17:33.285 --> 00:17:34.970
for rotation it's
angular momentum--

00:17:34.970 --> 00:17:36.380
commute with the energy.

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:38.860
And when you have an operator
that commutes with the energy

00:17:38.860 --> 00:17:41.350
operator, as we've
seen, you can generally

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:44.300
construct new states given
a single energy eigenstate

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:48.230
by acting suitably
with that operator.

00:17:48.230 --> 00:17:54.814
So we should expect there
to be some new symmetry.

00:17:54.814 --> 00:17:56.480
But it's very hard
to see what symmetry.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:58.287
I mean, this is hydrogen.

00:17:58.287 --> 00:17:59.370
This is central potential.

00:17:59.370 --> 00:18:01.100
It's just some stupid
central potential.

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:03.300
What's so special about
the hydrogen system as

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:05.650
opposed to, for example,
the harmonic oscillator?

00:18:05.650 --> 00:18:08.830
Which hopefully you will see
in recitation at some point.

00:18:08.830 --> 00:18:11.360
The harmonic oscillator
in three dimensions

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:13.590
has degeneracy 2l plus 1.

00:18:13.590 --> 00:18:14.650
It's a central potential.

00:18:14.650 --> 00:18:19.320
It has to have degeneracy 2l
plus 1-- but not n squared.

00:18:19.320 --> 00:18:20.370
Where did that come from?

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:22.290
What's so special about
the Kepler problem?

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:23.870
So there must be some
symmetry, but it's not obvious

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:24.640
what it is.

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:28.415
But now let's use a note
from classical mechanics.

00:18:28.415 --> 00:18:30.540
Noether's Theorem tells us
when we have a symmetry,

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:32.617
we have a conserved quantity.

00:18:32.617 --> 00:18:34.700
We also saw this in the
quantum mechanical version

00:18:34.700 --> 00:18:36.022
for expectation values.

00:18:36.022 --> 00:18:37.230
We have a conserved quantity.

00:18:41.632 --> 00:18:43.840
And in quantum mechanics,
having a conserved quantity

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:47.520
means that the energy
commutes with some quantity.

00:18:50.734 --> 00:18:52.400
Because that controls
the time evolution

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:53.441
of the expectation value.

00:18:55.739 --> 00:18:57.280
So there must be
some quantity, which

00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:00.440
I've written by a question mark,
that commutes with the energy

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:02.290
operator, specifically
in the case

00:19:02.290 --> 00:19:04.150
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:19:04.150 --> 00:19:05.529
So what is that quantity?

00:19:05.529 --> 00:19:07.570
So actually, this quantity
in classical mechanics

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:09.816
was studied, because
the same thing

00:19:09.816 --> 00:19:10.940
is true in the Kepler case.

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:13.230
In the Kepler case,
the orbits close,

00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:15.006
and they have simple
ellipses, and they

00:19:15.006 --> 00:19:16.380
have all sorts of
nice properties

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:18.869
that beg for an explanation
in terms of symmetry.

00:19:18.869 --> 00:19:21.160
And it was pointed out by a
number of people-- Laplace,

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:23.560
Runge, Lenz, various
people-- and this is often

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:25.020
called the Runge-Lenz
vector, but I

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:27.630
think you can blame it
on any number of people--

00:19:27.630 --> 00:19:30.740
that there's a vector that
in classical mechanics,

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:33.830
for the Kepler problem--
or for the Coulomb problem,

00:19:33.830 --> 00:19:35.200
is conserved.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:40.100
And that quantity is p cross
l-- momentum cross angular

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:46.825
momentum-- minus m
e squared-- and let

00:19:46.825 --> 00:19:49.290
me write m sub electrons--
it's the mass rather

00:19:49.290 --> 00:19:55.800
than the quantum number little
m-- e squared, r vector.

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:58.940
So it turns out this quantity
is classically conserved,

00:19:58.940 --> 00:20:01.280
and if you make a quantum
operator out of it,

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:05.260
then e with A is equal to 0.

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:07.582
Add hat.

00:20:07.582 --> 00:20:09.700
This was enormously non-obvious.

00:20:09.700 --> 00:20:12.800
If it's obvious to
you, you're a freak.

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:14.230
It's really, really not obvious.

00:20:14.230 --> 00:20:16.310
You can go through and
do the calculation.

00:20:16.310 --> 00:20:20.320
And when I say really not
obvious, I mean-- well,

00:20:20.320 --> 00:20:22.310
I'll show you what I
mean in just a second.

00:20:22.310 --> 00:20:24.825
So you can go through and do
the calculation classically.

00:20:24.825 --> 00:20:26.880
Is this quantity conserved
in the Kepler problem

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:27.520
using Newton's law?

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:28.110
And the answer is yes.

00:20:28.110 --> 00:20:28.920
It's amazing.

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:30.210
Quantum mechanically, you
can do the same thing.

00:20:30.210 --> 00:20:32.120
But I'm going to warn you for
anyone who has the chutzpah

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:33.620
to try-- because I
encourage you to,

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:36.280
but it takes a
little bit of brawn--

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:38.570
think about this
operator for second.

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:42.019
Does this classical quantity
have an obvious interpretation

00:20:42.019 --> 00:20:42.935
as a quantum operator?

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:49.230
No, because l is r cross p.

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:50.940
But now we have prp.

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:52.770
There's an ordering ambiguity.

00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:54.730
So you have to decide
which order do you

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:58.020
put that p and that r, and
the other p-- ppr, rpr,

00:20:58.020 --> 00:20:59.469
prr-- right?

00:20:59.469 --> 00:21:01.510
You can write out which
components you mean here.

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:04.140
For example, you mean
for the z component of a,

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:08.090
you're going to get
px ly, and ly px.

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:12.460
But within that, how do you
order the p's and the r's,

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:19.510
because ly contains px, and
in particular, it contains x.

00:21:19.510 --> 00:21:21.860
So there's an
ordering ambiguity.

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:25.130
So just be a little bit
careful about this as a quantum

00:21:25.130 --> 00:21:27.470
mechanical operator if
you do play with this.

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:30.050
But if you do it, and
you're thoughtful about it,

00:21:30.050 --> 00:21:32.850
it's pretty easy to see that
it can be computed and checked

00:21:32.850 --> 00:21:35.090
that, in fact, the
commutator vanishes.

00:21:35.090 --> 00:21:37.311
So at this point, it's
tempting to say, aha!

00:21:37.311 --> 00:21:38.810
There's an extra
conserved quantity.

00:21:38.810 --> 00:21:40.180
We declare victory.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:42.980
The problem is, this didn't
give us the symmetry.

00:21:42.980 --> 00:21:44.960
This just told us there's
a conserved quantity.

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:48.361
What's the symmetry behind this?

00:21:48.361 --> 00:21:50.110
What's the symmetry
that insures that this

00:21:50.110 --> 00:21:52.070
is a conserved quantity?

00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:53.630
It's obviously not rotations.

00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:56.240
It's something else.

00:21:56.240 --> 00:21:58.400
And so there are many
answers to this question.

00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:02.840
One answer involves an explicit
expression for in phase space,

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:05.930
the change of
variables dx-- and this

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:15.730
is a variation that
depends on f of x and p.

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:17.560
So there's a little
vector parameter,

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:22.060
and the change of the
physical coordinates

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:24.796
depends on both the
coordinates and the momenta.

00:22:24.796 --> 00:22:26.170
This is a slightly
strange thing,

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:27.450
because it's like a
change of variables

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:29.949
where the position gets mapped
into some non-linear function

00:22:29.949 --> 00:22:31.590
of the positions and momenta.

00:22:31.590 --> 00:22:34.580
That's a little bit weird,
but you can do this.

00:22:34.580 --> 00:22:36.622
But I don't find it a
terribly satisfying answer.

00:22:36.622 --> 00:22:38.913
And here's the answer I find
most satisfying-- it's not

00:22:38.913 --> 00:22:40.700
terribly useful for
our present purposes,

00:22:40.700 --> 00:22:43.520
but you're going to run
into this again in 805, when

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:46.717
you do what's called the
operator method for the Coulomb

00:22:46.717 --> 00:22:48.092
potential, and it
turns out to be

00:22:48.092 --> 00:22:49.686
an enormously useful machine.

00:22:49.686 --> 00:22:51.060
We're not going
to use it in 804,

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:52.610
but I want to
advertise it for you.

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:53.590
I want to give you a
description, though,

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:55.950
that isn't the description
you're going to get in 805.

00:22:55.950 --> 00:22:59.280
The description is
the following-- 1935,

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.880
guy named Fock,
crazy guy, amazing,

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:03.820
amazing physicist--
played a huge role

00:23:03.820 --> 00:23:05.660
in the development of
quantum field theory.

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:08.290
I'm not exactly sure why he was
thinking about this problem,

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:12.500
but he was, and this was a
very sort of Soviet thing

00:23:12.500 --> 00:23:15.150
to do at the time, I guess, to
be hard core and mathematical.

00:23:15.150 --> 00:23:18.200
So off he was going,
computing things,

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:19.870
and he observed the
following fact--

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:23.260
how he observed this,
again, crazy long story.

00:23:23.260 --> 00:23:26.170
He observed the following fact--
if you take a Kepler problem

00:23:26.170 --> 00:23:29.010
and you work in momentum
space-- so you write everything

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:32.430
in terms of the momentum--
it turns out that the Kepler

00:23:32.430 --> 00:23:36.370
problem, or he referred
to as the Kepler problem,

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:41.986
but I'll refer to it as
the Coulomb problem in 3D,

00:23:41.986 --> 00:23:45.610
three spatial dimensions--
this is really crazy--

00:23:45.610 --> 00:23:47.060
is exactly equivalent.

00:23:47.060 --> 00:23:50.202
There's a change of variables--
it's kind of complicated,

00:23:50.202 --> 00:23:51.910
but it's just a
projection, it turns out.

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:58.980
It's exactly equivalent to
the problem of a free particle

00:23:58.980 --> 00:24:07.320
in four dimensions,
constrained to the surface

00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:11.274
of a sphere-- to a three
sphere in four dimensions.

00:24:11.274 --> 00:24:13.190
So you take a three
sphere in four dimensions.

00:24:13.190 --> 00:24:14.090
You take a marble.

00:24:14.090 --> 00:24:17.060
You kick it, but make sure
that it's stuck to the sphere.

00:24:17.060 --> 00:24:18.900
It will move in
perfect circles, right?

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.400
Obviously-- it's
moving on a sphere,

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:22.110
it's just going to
move in great circles.

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:23.910
OK, that's nice and simple.

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:26.950
What's the symmetry
group of that system?

00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:29.060
Well, the sphere is
invariant under any rotation

00:24:29.060 --> 00:24:31.780
in four dimensions.

00:24:31.780 --> 00:24:32.980
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:36.924
PROFESSOR: Ah, SO4--
there's a symmetry SO4--

00:24:36.924 --> 00:24:38.340
special orthogonal
transformation.

00:24:38.340 --> 00:24:39.965
Special means it
doesn't change length.

00:24:39.965 --> 00:24:41.730
Orthogonal means
that it's a rotation.

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:44.930
So it's orthogonal rotations
in four dimensions,

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:49.060
and so now, this
should sound familiar,

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:57.780
because the angular
momentum group in 3D is SO3.

00:24:57.780 --> 00:25:01.580
It's rotations that don't change
the length in three dimensions.

00:25:01.580 --> 00:25:02.080
OK?

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:04.050
How many elements does it have?

00:25:04.050 --> 00:25:06.587
How many conserved quantities
go along with this?

00:25:06.587 --> 00:25:08.420
Well, how many conserved
quantities go along

00:25:08.420 --> 00:25:09.878
with rotations in
three dimensions?

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:14.510
What's conserved by virtue of
rotational invariance in three

00:25:14.510 --> 00:25:15.350
dimensions?

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:17.766
Angular momentum-- how many
components of angular momentum

00:25:17.766 --> 00:25:18.500
are there?

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:19.880
Three, right, there are three.

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:23.420
So it turns out that
if you calculate in SO4

00:25:23.420 --> 00:25:27.690
how many conserved quantities
are there, there are six.

00:25:27.690 --> 00:25:29.430
And when you do this
mapping back down

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:32.510
from the free particle in 4D
to the Coulomb problem in 3D,

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:36.780
three of them are the l's,
and the other three of them

00:25:36.780 --> 00:25:41.280
are this A vector--
comes out spot on.

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:44.447
So what it's telling you is
that the spectrum of hydrogen--

00:25:44.447 --> 00:25:46.280
or at least the I
shouldn't say of hydrogen,

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:48.370
the spectrum of the
Coulomb system--

00:25:48.370 --> 00:25:50.350
has an enhanced symmetry.

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:54.060
It's the symmetry group of
rotations in four dimensions.

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:55.990
Why?

00:25:55.990 --> 00:25:57.790
I don't know, it's
just kind awesome.

00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:01.220
But I think that's about
the best that can be said.

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:02.510
It's just true.

00:26:02.510 --> 00:26:04.170
So for certain very
special potentials,

00:26:04.170 --> 00:26:05.836
we find that this
sort of thing happens.

00:26:05.836 --> 00:26:07.230
It happens in
other systems, too.

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:09.500
You discover that there
are accidental symmetries

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:10.379
in your system.

00:26:10.379 --> 00:26:12.670
They shouldn't be referred
to as accidental symmetries.

00:26:12.670 --> 00:26:14.970
They are enormously
nontrivial functions

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:16.774
of the rest of the
system, and we're

00:26:16.774 --> 00:26:18.440
going to break the
symmetry in a minute,

00:26:18.440 --> 00:26:20.856
and you'll see why we shouldn't
refer to it as accidental.

00:26:20.856 --> 00:26:23.080
But in any case, the
answer to the question,

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:26.240
why do we have this giant
degeneracy in the Coulomb

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:28.900
problem-- why is it n squared
rather than 2l plus 1--

00:26:28.900 --> 00:26:31.407
is that there is an
enhanced symmetry group.

00:26:31.407 --> 00:26:33.490
There's more symmetry then
you would have thought.

00:26:33.490 --> 00:26:35.980
And there's a conserved
quantity associated with it.

00:26:35.980 --> 00:26:37.790
And that conserved
quantity corresponds

00:26:37.790 --> 00:26:39.910
quantum mechanically
to an operator

00:26:39.910 --> 00:26:43.070
that commutes with
the energy operator.

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:44.018
OK?

00:26:44.018 --> 00:26:46.030
Yeah.

00:26:46.030 --> 00:26:46.946
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:52.330 --> 00:26:53.521
PROFESSOR: Indeed, indeed.

00:26:53.521 --> 00:26:55.770
AUDIENCE: So how do you get
three conserved components

00:26:55.770 --> 00:26:57.995
[INAUDIBLE].

00:26:57.995 --> 00:26:58.870
PROFESSOR: Excellent.

00:26:58.870 --> 00:27:01.770
What do I mean in classical
mechanics for a quantity

00:27:01.770 --> 00:27:02.932
to be conserved?

00:27:02.932 --> 00:27:05.140
I mean that the time rate
of change of that quantity,

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.620
under the classical dynamics,
under classical evolution,

00:27:07.620 --> 00:27:09.990
is preserved.

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:13.600
So what's the quantum
mechanical version of that?

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:15.520
So the mechanical
version of that is, well,

00:27:15.520 --> 00:27:21.310
can we say that d dt
of some operator--

00:27:21.310 --> 00:27:23.740
or of some observable a is 0.

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:25.210
Does this makes sense?

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:28.740
No, because it turns out,
in the language we've

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:31.410
