00:34:14.909 --> 00:34:18.679
OK, so everyone cool
with the degeneracy?

00:34:18.679 --> 00:34:20.110
We have this
gigantic degeneracy.

00:34:20.110 --> 00:34:23.409
So knowing what the degeneracy
is, or where it's coming from,

00:34:23.409 --> 00:34:26.199
at least more or
less-- is progress.

00:34:26.199 --> 00:34:29.630
But if you really understand
why something is conserved,

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:31.989
then you can break
that conservation.

00:34:31.989 --> 00:34:33.590
You can break that degeneracy.

00:34:33.590 --> 00:34:37.190
So here's my question,
is it possible-- can

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:46.240
we, or indeed must we, can we
break or lift this degeneracy?

00:34:46.240 --> 00:34:48.239
So first, let me tell you
what those words mean.

00:34:51.350 --> 00:35:00.130
So we have this
gigantic degeneracy

00:35:00.130 --> 00:35:04.504
of the n squared of
the Coulomb potential.

00:35:04.504 --> 00:35:06.170
Can we break that
degeneracy or lift it?

00:35:06.170 --> 00:35:08.461
What I mean by lift the
degeneracy, what I mean by lift

00:35:08.461 --> 00:35:09.837
the degeneracy is
the following--

00:35:09.837 --> 00:35:11.586
suppose I have a system
that's degenerate,

00:35:11.586 --> 00:35:13.090
so it's got two
energy eigenstates

00:35:13.090 --> 00:35:14.440
with the same energy eigenvalue.

00:35:14.440 --> 00:35:16.330
So this is energy.

00:35:16.330 --> 00:35:18.256
Then if I can kick the
system in some way,

00:35:18.256 --> 00:35:20.830
or modify it, or bend it such
that the energy levels are

00:35:20.830 --> 00:35:23.580
no longer to
degenerate, one state

00:35:23.580 --> 00:35:25.137
has been lifted above the other.

00:35:25.137 --> 00:35:26.970
And so we use the word
to lift a degeneracy.

00:35:26.970 --> 00:35:29.011
Now you can see that
they're two different states

00:35:29.011 --> 00:35:30.300
by measuring the energies.

00:35:30.300 --> 00:35:32.330
It's also said to
split a degeneracy,

00:35:32.330 --> 00:35:33.790
or to break a degeneracy.

00:35:33.790 --> 00:35:35.117
So those are just words.

00:35:35.117 --> 00:35:36.950
OK, so can we break or
lift this degeneracy?

00:35:40.170 --> 00:35:40.792
So sure.

00:35:40.792 --> 00:35:42.000
How do we break a degeneracy?

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:43.210
How do we lift a degeneracy?

00:35:46.610 --> 00:35:47.860
We need to break the symmetry.

00:35:54.825 --> 00:35:56.200
So if we don't
have the symmetry,

00:35:56.200 --> 00:35:57.366
we won't get the degeneracy.

00:35:57.366 --> 00:35:58.630
We've seen this before.

00:35:58.630 --> 00:36:01.100
So first off, let's
think about what

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:02.600
are the two symmetries
that we want?

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:04.660
Well, we got this
degeneracy of 2l plus 1

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:06.650
from spherical symmetry.

00:36:06.650 --> 00:36:10.210
And we got this extra degeneracy
of n squared from conservation

00:36:10.210 --> 00:36:11.550
of the Runge-Lenz vector.

00:36:11.550 --> 00:36:13.300
And conservation of
the Runge-Lenz vector

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:16.400
came from the fact that we had
exactly the Coulomb system.

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:18.940
So anything that isn't
exactly the Coulomb system,

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:21.470
but is still
rotationally invariant,

00:36:21.470 --> 00:36:23.280
should still have the
2l plus 1 degeneracy,

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:25.260
but not the n
squared degeneracy--

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:28.060
like the harmonic
oscillator, for example.

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:29.800
So let's change the system.

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:33.330
Let's find a small correction
to the system that leaves it

00:36:33.330 --> 00:36:36.080
mostly the Coulomb problem,
but with some small correction.

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:40.830
So what comes to mind?

00:36:40.830 --> 00:36:45.290
So one good way to think
about a physical, natural way

00:36:45.290 --> 00:36:47.380
to break this degeneracy,
to break the symmetry,

00:36:47.380 --> 00:36:49.555
is to think a real system
that's described by the Coulomb

00:36:49.555 --> 00:36:50.055
potential.

00:36:50.055 --> 00:36:52.330
So the system that we usually
talk about is hydrogen.

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:53.444
Hydrogen is the proton.

00:36:53.444 --> 00:36:55.360
It's got a plus charge,
and it's got electron.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:58.510
And it's attractive with
a minus E squared upon r.

00:36:58.510 --> 00:37:03.239
So in hydrogen, is this the
energy operator for hydrogen?

00:37:03.239 --> 00:37:05.280
Is this a good description
of the energy operator

00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:08.120
for hydrogen?

00:37:08.120 --> 00:37:10.632
It's a good start, but
it's not exactly right,

00:37:10.632 --> 00:37:11.590
for a bunch of reasons.

00:37:11.590 --> 00:37:13.620
And in fact, in your
first problem set,

00:37:13.620 --> 00:37:15.980
when you computed the time
it takes for hydrogen,

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:23.564
classically, to decay from
the classical Bohr radius,

00:37:23.564 --> 00:37:26.230
one of the things you discovered
is that the electron starts out

00:37:26.230 --> 00:37:30.330
being non-relativistic, but very
rapidly becomes relativistic.

00:37:30.330 --> 00:37:34.030
And rapidly is 10 to
the minus 15 seconds.

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:37.850
This is a non-relativistic, p
squared upon 2m kinetic energy.

00:37:37.850 --> 00:37:40.820
That's probably not a
perfect approximation.

00:37:40.820 --> 00:37:48.020
So the first example is going
to be relativistic corrections.

00:37:48.020 --> 00:37:49.510
Now, will relativistic
corrections

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:50.595
break rotational symmetry?

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:56.370
They can't, because
relativity doesn't say,

00:37:56.370 --> 00:37:57.580
this is the z direction.

00:37:57.580 --> 00:37:59.080
In fact, it does
quite the opposite.

00:37:59.080 --> 00:38:00.621
Relativity, among
other things, says,

00:38:00.621 --> 00:38:02.880
don't get too hung up on
what's the z direction.

00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:05.920
But relativistic corrections
will not break the symmetry.

00:38:05.920 --> 00:38:13.420
So if we include
relativistic corrections

00:38:13.420 --> 00:38:20.270
to the kinetic energy,
this will change E,

00:38:20.270 --> 00:38:21.910
change the energy operator.

00:38:21.910 --> 00:38:27.740
But it will preserve
the rotational symmetry.

00:38:27.740 --> 00:38:30.899
E with l is equal to 0.

00:38:30.899 --> 00:38:32.690
So we won't break this
rotational symmetry,

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.160
so we'll preserve the 2l plus 1.

00:38:34.160 --> 00:38:36.890
So let's check to see
that this is true.

00:38:36.890 --> 00:38:38.940
So to check to see
that this is true,

00:38:38.940 --> 00:38:44.950
let's actually estimate out
the correction to the energy

00:38:44.950 --> 00:38:48.640
due to the first nontrivial
relativistic effect

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:50.000
in the atom.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:51.970
The first nontrivial,
relativistic effect

00:38:51.970 --> 00:38:54.220
can be calculated
[INAUDIBLE] kinetic energy

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:57.780
in special relativity,
of a particle of mass m.

00:38:57.780 --> 00:38:58.650
So that's easy.

00:38:58.650 --> 00:39:06.130
It's the total energy is
the square root of m squared

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:12.842
c to the 4th plus p squared
c squared minus mc squared.

00:39:12.842 --> 00:39:13.800
That's the rest energy.

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:17.830
That's the total energy, so
this is the kinetic energy.

00:39:17.830 --> 00:39:20.360
But this is equal to--
well, if we pull out

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:21.925
a factor of m squared
c squared, this

00:39:21.925 --> 00:39:31.550
is m c squared times the square
root of 1 plus p squared over n

00:39:31.550 --> 00:39:36.054
squared c squared minus 1.

00:39:36.054 --> 00:39:37.470
And now if we
Taylor expand this--

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:42.100
because if the momentum is small
compared to mc squared-- or mc,

00:39:42.100 --> 00:39:44.850
I should say-- the momentum is
small compared to mc which is,

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:47.170
morally speaking,
at low velocity is,

00:39:47.170 --> 00:39:48.870
the velocity is
small compared to c,

00:39:48.870 --> 00:39:51.070
then this is 1 plus
a small number,

00:39:51.070 --> 00:39:56.120
and we can Taylor expand this to
get 1 plus 1/2 a small number.

00:39:56.120 --> 00:39:58.060
And the 1s will cancel,
giving us only 1/2.

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:01.630
So this is going to be equal
to 1/2 of that small number,

00:40:01.630 --> 00:40:05.610
p squared over m
squared c squared,

00:40:05.610 --> 00:40:07.820
times mc squared
upstairs, giving us

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:10.100
the first term, which
is p squared upon 2m.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:12.360
That's the familiar
classical kinetic energy.

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:13.170
Rock on.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:14.320
What's next correction?

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:16.400
The next correction is the next
term for this Taylor series,

00:40:16.400 --> 00:40:18.110
which is going to involve
this quantity squared,

00:40:18.110 --> 00:40:20.470
so it's going to be p to
the 4th over m to the 4th, c

00:40:20.470 --> 00:40:22.830
the 4th times mc to the 4th.

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:25.760
The coefficient is a minus
1/8, so we get minus p

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:31.790
to the 4th over 8m
cubed c squared.

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:38.780
And that's down by a
factor of m squared

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:40.900
c squared from this
guy, n of p squared

00:40:40.900 --> 00:40:42.750
upstairs-- which is
what you'd get-- p

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:45.080
squared m squared,
over c squared, OK?

00:40:45.080 --> 00:40:47.890
So the correction to the kinetic
energy for a given momentum p

00:40:47.890 --> 00:40:51.490
is to correct it down
by p to the 4th term.

00:40:51.490 --> 00:40:52.580
Everyone cool with that?

00:40:52.580 --> 00:40:54.418
Yeah.

00:40:54.418 --> 00:40:58.150
AUDIENCE: Why do you make
the assumption [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:58.150 --> 00:41:00.390
PROFESSOR: Because
you, like Schrodinger,

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:02.580
did problem Set One.

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:06.050
And problem Set One said, if
you have an electron at the Bohr

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:09.530
radius classically, its
velocity is about 1/400

00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:10.910
of the speed of light.

00:41:10.910 --> 00:41:12.350
200?

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:13.005
It's small.

00:41:13.005 --> 00:41:14.505
It's a couple of
orders of magnitude

00:41:14.505 --> 00:41:15.838
smaller than the speed of light.

00:41:15.838 --> 00:41:19.890
So that number, that ratio
there, is 1 upon 200,

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:21.462
or 400-- I don't
remember-- squared.

00:41:21.462 --> 00:41:22.920
That's a very small
number, so it's

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:24.210
a reasonable approximation.

00:41:24.210 --> 00:41:26.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:28.510
PROFESSOR: Because what
is the typical-- that's

00:41:28.510 --> 00:41:29.150
an excellent question.

00:41:29.150 --> 00:41:31.108
So why am I talking about
it as if the electron

00:41:31.108 --> 00:41:32.600
is sitting at that radius?

00:41:32.600 --> 00:41:36.680
And the answer is, well, look--
what is the average momentum?

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:39.299
What is the average
value of p squared in,

00:41:39.299 --> 00:41:41.340
let's say, the ground
state of the hydrogen atom?

00:41:41.340 --> 00:41:42.589
What's the average value of p?

00:41:45.650 --> 00:41:47.150
What must be the
average value of p

00:41:47.150 --> 00:41:49.570
in the ground state
of the hydrogen atom?

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:52.090
Zero on two grounds--
first off, p is a vector,

00:41:52.090 --> 00:41:54.580
and the ground state of hydrogen
is rotationally invariant.

00:41:54.580 --> 00:41:55.663
It doesn't break anything.

00:41:55.663 --> 00:41:57.630
Secondly, it's not
going anywhere.

00:41:57.630 --> 00:41:59.588
It's a bound state, so
it's just sitting there.

00:41:59.588 --> 00:42:01.640
It's got an average
momentum of 0.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:03.980
If it carried momentum,
it would be cruising.

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:05.470
So it's got average momentum 0.

00:42:05.470 --> 00:42:07.553
OK, fine, but what's the
average momentum squared?

00:42:07.553 --> 00:42:09.414
What's the average of p squared?

00:42:09.414 --> 00:42:11.080
We can actually do
out that calculation.

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:13.705
You're going to have to do that
calculation on the problem set.

00:42:13.705 --> 00:42:15.315
And it's a small number.

00:42:15.315 --> 00:42:17.190
And it's, in fact,
almost exactly what

00:42:17.190 --> 00:42:19.890
you'd guess classically
from the Bohr radius.

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:22.456
So you have to know the
h bar to compute the Bohr

00:42:22.456 --> 00:42:24.040
radius in the first place.

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:26.530
So the answer is, to the
best of anyone's ability

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:29.559
to define what's the
momentum, or the typical scale

00:42:29.559 --> 00:42:31.350
of momentum, that
typical scale of momentum

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:32.850
for the electron in the
ground state of hydrogen

00:42:32.850 --> 00:42:35.340
is extraordinarily small
compared to the speed of light

00:42:35.340 --> 00:42:37.749
by a factor of 100, 200, or 400.

00:42:37.749 --> 00:42:39.040
Does that answer your question?

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:39.270
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:40.811
PROFESSOR: It's a
very good question.

00:42:40.811 --> 00:42:42.750
OK, so here's the
kinetic energy.

00:42:42.750 --> 00:42:44.881
And by the way,
another way to say

00:42:44.881 --> 00:42:46.380
that this approximation
must be good

00:42:46.380 --> 00:42:48.080
is that we've already
computed-- ignoring

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:50.246
the relativistic correction--
we computed the ground

00:42:50.246 --> 00:42:52.070
state of energy,
and it was 13.6 Ev,

00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:55.450
which is pretty good, since
the binding energy of hydrogen

00:42:55.450 --> 00:42:57.370
is about 13.6 Ev.

00:42:57.370 --> 00:42:59.640
So apparently, that was
a good approximation.

00:42:59.640 --> 00:43:02.160
And you might be disgusted
by answer analysis like that,

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:04.117
but that's what physics is.

00:43:04.117 --> 00:43:05.950
You write down some
stupid, cockamamie model

00:43:05.950 --> 00:43:07.350
that you know is
wrong, but if it

00:43:07.350 --> 00:43:10.522
does a good job of fitting
the data, you declare triumph,

00:43:10.522 --> 00:43:11.480
and you call Stockholm.

00:43:11.480 --> 00:43:13.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:17.300
So it depends on the
problem you've just

00:43:17.300 --> 00:43:19.210
solved approximately.

00:43:19.210 --> 00:43:24.080
So here's the first correction.

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:26.570
And now, what this
tells us is therefore,

00:43:26.570 --> 00:43:29.675
the energy of
hydrogen-- or at least

00:43:29.675 --> 00:43:31.050
a better model of
hydrogen-- I'll

00:43:31.050 --> 00:43:37.070
call it hydrogen tilde--
is equal to E Coulomb

00:43:37.070 --> 00:43:43.450
minus p to the 4th over
8m cubed c squared.

00:43:53.540 --> 00:43:56.870
OK so this, however, we
know is small compared

00:43:56.870 --> 00:44:00.812
to the kinetic energy, because
13.6 is pretty close to 13.6.

00:44:00.812 --> 00:44:03.270
Notice I didn't include the
rest of the significant digits.

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:07.010
So this must be in the
insignificant digits.

00:44:07.010 --> 00:44:08.460
So this must be small.

00:44:08.460 --> 00:44:10.460
So here's what I
want to ask-- we

00:44:10.460 --> 00:44:14.400
know that the energy of
the Coulomb problem, nlm,

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:17.660
is equal to e0 squared
minus e0 squared

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:21.400
over n squared,
independent of l and m.

00:44:21.400 --> 00:44:25.090
What's the energy in this
toy model of hydrogen

00:44:25.090 --> 00:44:29.580
that includes the first
relativistic correction-- nlm.

00:44:29.580 --> 00:44:32.436
Well, to answer that question
we have to resolve the energy

00:44:32.436 --> 00:44:33.560
eigenvalue equation, right?

00:44:33.560 --> 00:44:35.310
We have to refined the
energy eigenstates,

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:36.610
and we have to solve that.

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:38.410
And this is going to be a much
worse problem, because it's

00:44:38.410 --> 00:44:40.201
going to involve a p
to the 4th term, which

00:44:40.201 --> 00:44:41.820
is going to involve
four derivatives.

00:44:41.820 --> 00:44:44.580
That sounds horrible.

00:44:44.580 --> 00:44:47.040
Can anyone think of a better
way to just approximate,

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:50.640
estimate the magnitude and the
value of the leading correction

00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:53.163
from this quantity?

00:44:53.163 --> 00:44:53.663
Yeah.

00:44:56.960 --> 00:45:00.865
AUDIENCE: Some variation
on take an eigenvalue,

00:45:00.865 --> 00:45:03.933
plug it in, see
what the error is,

00:45:03.933 --> 00:45:06.630
correct for that error--
something like that.

00:45:06.630 --> 00:45:08.880
PROFESSOR: There's an iterative
method for doing that.

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:10.880
It's a very good guess, but
there's an even easier way

00:45:10.880 --> 00:45:11.505
to estimate it.

00:45:11.505 --> 00:45:15.320
That's something we will
call perturbation theory when

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:16.640
we do this in 805.

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:19.419
And doing that systematically
is exactly the right answer.

00:45:19.419 --> 00:45:21.710
However I want you to do just
the leading part of that.

00:45:21.710 --> 00:45:22.110
Yeah.

00:45:22.110 --> 00:45:23.310
AUDIENCE: Dimensional analysis.

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:25.518
PROFESSOR: Oh, dimensional
analysis would be awesome.

00:45:25.518 --> 00:45:29.080
That's fantastic, brilliant.

00:45:29.080 --> 00:45:30.387
So how would you compute p?

00:45:34.123 --> 00:45:35.570
OK, so we didn't calculate p.

00:45:35.570 --> 00:45:36.560
You can do a
dimensional analysis

00:45:36.560 --> 00:45:38.018
and get a p, because
you have an e,

00:45:38.018 --> 00:45:39.630
you have an l, you
can probably do it.

00:45:39.630 --> 00:45:41.004
But here's the
problem with that,

00:45:41.004 --> 00:45:43.530
though-- this is the correct
first answer to any question

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:45.230
of this kind--
correct first answer

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:47.826
is plug in dimensional
analysis, and get an estimate

00:45:47.826 --> 00:45:48.950
for the order of magnitude.

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:52.030
But we want more than the
order of magnitude here.

00:45:52.030 --> 00:45:54.760
We're interested in
splitting the degeneracy

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:56.154
due to this interaction.

00:45:56.154 --> 00:45:58.570
So what that means is we want
to see that different values

00:45:58.570 --> 00:46:01.330
use of l lead to
different energy.

00:46:01.330 --> 00:46:03.560
What we care about
is the l dependence

00:46:03.560 --> 00:46:04.980
that comes out of
this correction.

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:07.230
And we're not going to be
able to get the l dependence

00:46:07.230 --> 00:46:10.390
from dimensional analysis,
because l is an integer.

00:46:10.390 --> 00:46:12.300
It is dimensionless.

00:46:12.300 --> 00:46:14.750
Yeah, so that will give
you the correct magnitude,

00:46:14.750 --> 00:46:17.220
and that is the
first thing you do.

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:18.934
What's the second thing you do?

00:46:18.934 --> 00:46:20.600
AUDIENCE: Stick in
the expectation value

00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:21.365
of p to the 4th.

00:46:21.365 --> 00:46:22.240
PROFESSOR: Excellent.

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:24.670
Let's just stick in the
expectation value p to the 4th.

00:46:24.670 --> 00:46:26.420
That's not exactly
the right thing to do,

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:28.987
but if this is small, that's
probably pretty reasonable.

00:46:28.987 --> 00:46:31.320
And what you'll find when you
do it systematically using

00:46:31.320 --> 00:46:33.520
perturbation theory, as
was pointed out earlier,

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:36.780
we can take the entire system,
the entire energy eigenvalue

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:38.800
equation-- we can
think of this 1 over m

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:41.439
cubed c squared
as a small number,

00:46:41.439 --> 00:46:43.730
and we can do perturbation
theory on that small number.

00:46:43.730 --> 00:46:46.120
We can Taylor expand everything
in that small number.

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:48.690
And when you Taylor expand
the exact equation, what

00:46:48.690 --> 00:46:52.470
you discover is the leading
term in that Taylor expansion

00:46:52.470 --> 00:46:55.040
is the expectation value
p to the 4th over 8m cubed

00:46:55.040 --> 00:46:56.260
c squared.

00:46:56.260 --> 00:46:57.970
OK, so this is a
fantastic guess.

00:46:57.970 --> 00:46:59.490
OK, so let's compute it.

00:46:59.490 --> 00:47:02.930
So E hydrogen is going to be
equal to E nlm, which I'm just

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:06.020
to write as minus
E0 over m squared.

00:47:23.600 --> 00:47:27.210
OK, so what is the
correct answer here?

00:47:27.210 --> 00:47:30.450
So it's this quantity
minus-- so this

00:47:30.450 --> 00:47:31.940
is making it more tightly bound.

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:33.790
Notice the sign,
because p to the 4th

00:47:33.790 --> 00:47:36.770
is strictly positive
if p is real.

00:47:36.770 --> 00:47:38.670
So minus E0 over m
squared, and if you go out

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:40.711
and you do this expectation
value, which I really

00:47:40.711 --> 00:47:43.839
should have put on the
problem set-- oh, I still can.

00:47:43.839 --> 00:47:46.380
It hasn't been posted yet, so
it'll be posted this afternoon.

00:47:46.380 --> 00:47:48.600
But I won't.

00:47:48.600 --> 00:47:51.450
It's not that bad, actually.

00:47:51.450 --> 00:47:53.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:53.680 --> 00:47:54.923
Matt, what do you think?

00:47:54.923 --> 00:47:56.855
AUDIENCE: No!

00:47:56.855 --> 00:48:00.240
[LAUGHS]

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:02.680
PROFESSOR: We'll discuss
this afterwards, OK?

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:05.299
Which may or may not
appear on your problem set.

00:48:05.299 --> 00:48:07.840
So if you go ahead and you do
this calculation, what you find

00:48:07.840 --> 00:48:12.497
is the correction is En
squared, so E0 squared over n

00:48:12.497 --> 00:48:14.580
to the 4th-- this time it
really is n to the 4th--

00:48:14.580 --> 00:48:16.370
and now you have to worry
about dimensional analysis.

00:48:16.370 --> 00:48:17.400
This is two energies.

00:48:17.400 --> 00:48:20.806
We want one energy, divided
by-- wait for it-- mc squared,

00:48:20.806 --> 00:48:22.430
because it's a
relativistic correction.

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:24.110
That shouldn't be
too surprising.

00:48:24.110 --> 00:48:27.765
Times the quantity
4n over-- and here

00:48:27.765 --> 00:48:32.932
where life gets awesome--
l plus 1/2 minus 3.

00:48:32.932 --> 00:48:37.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:37.550 --> 00:48:40.990
PROFESSOR: You laugh,
but I feel delighted

00:48:40.990 --> 00:48:42.480
by this for so many reasons.

00:48:42.480 --> 00:48:44.090
One is, that's beautiful.

00:48:44.090 --> 00:48:45.650
What a crazy
combination of symbols.

00:48:45.650 --> 00:48:47.100
But the second
and more important

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:52.390
one is, look it has an l in it,
and the l is downstairs, right?

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:53.891
That's good.

00:48:53.891 --> 00:48:55.140
It has more leverage that way.

00:48:55.140 --> 00:48:57.960
But so we've got
this l appearing,

00:48:57.960 --> 00:49:01.780
so the energy depends on l.

00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:03.200
Good, we've broken
the degeneracy.

00:49:03.200 --> 00:49:05.957
Different values of l
give different energies.

00:49:05.957 --> 00:49:07.165
So let's do that graphically.

00:49:12.510 --> 00:49:17.130
So in particular,
what this tells

00:49:17.130 --> 00:49:23.780
us is that now while the
Coulomb energy commuted

00:49:23.780 --> 00:49:26.950
with the Runge-Lenz
vector, it must be true

00:49:26.950 --> 00:49:29.960
that the energy of
this model of hydrogen,

00:49:29.960 --> 00:49:33.620
which includes the first
relativistic correction,

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:36.960
does not commute with
the Runge-Lenz vector.

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:38.810
And indeed, if you
check this-- which

00:49:38.810 --> 00:49:42.160
is effortful, but
not intellectually

00:49:42.160 --> 00:49:45.870
difficult-- indeed,
it doesn't vanish.

00:49:45.870 --> 00:49:48.540
And the failure of this
conservation equation,

00:49:48.540 --> 00:49:52.430
the failure this commutational
relation to vanish,

00:49:52.430 --> 00:49:54.720
tell us that it's
possible for the system

00:49:54.720 --> 00:49:55.760
to not be degenerate.

00:49:55.760 --> 00:49:58.430
And lo and behold,
it is not degenerate.

00:49:58.430 --> 00:49:59.680
OK?

00:49:59.680 --> 00:50:00.500
Yeah.

00:50:00.500 --> 00:50:03.120
AUDIENCE: So I just wanted
to clarify something that--

00:50:03.120 --> 00:50:06.424
did you say before that the
actual first term when you

00:50:06.424 --> 00:50:08.532
encounter relativity just
includes substituting

00:50:08.532 --> 00:50:11.516
the non-relativistic
p to the 4th?

00:50:11.516 --> 00:50:12.140
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:13.010
Sorry, I should have said that.

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:15.190
There are other things are
important for relativity

00:50:15.190 --> 00:50:16.648
that we'll come to
in a little bit.

00:50:16.648 --> 00:50:18.700
But if you just look
at the kinetic energy,

00:50:18.700 --> 00:50:21.172
this is the first
non-trivial correction.

00:50:21.172 --> 00:50:23.020
Yeah.

00:50:23.020 --> 00:50:25.330
AUDIENCE: So we still have
the 2l plus 1 degeneracy.

00:50:25.330 --> 00:50:27.950
PROFESSOR: We still have the
2l plus 1 degeneracy, exactly.

00:50:27.950 --> 00:50:31.796
Because does this correction
violate rotational invariance?

00:50:31.796 --> 00:50:32.670
No, that's p squared.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:33.961
That's a scalar under rotation.

00:50:33.961 --> 00:50:36.070
It's just the
number, not a vector.

00:50:36.070 --> 00:50:42.320
But E still commutes with l.

00:50:42.320 --> 00:50:45.310
And you see that because this
is independent of little m.

00:50:45.310 --> 00:50:47.160
This is the mass
of the electron.

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:49.460
So this is independent of
the quantum number little m.

00:50:49.460 --> 00:50:53.630
It only depends on the
quantum number little l.

00:50:53.630 --> 00:50:55.220
So indeed, it is
still degenerate.

00:50:55.220 --> 00:50:58.997
So let's go through this and
see the degeneracy explicitly.

00:50:58.997 --> 00:51:01.330
And let me do that by drawing
you the following diagram.

00:51:01.330 --> 00:51:08.780
So what happens if we have
E1, which is the ground state?

00:51:08.780 --> 00:51:13.670
It has some energy which is
negative, which is minus E0.

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:17.700
And when we include this first
correction, what does it do?

00:51:17.700 --> 00:51:19.542
Well, it decreases
it by some amount.

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:23.962
Everyone cool with that?

00:51:23.962 --> 00:51:25.170
It doesn't change the number.

00:51:25.170 --> 00:51:26.860
It doesn't split any degeneracy,
because there was only

00:51:26.860 --> 00:51:28.360
one ground state
in the first place,

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:30.590
because l had to
be 0 when n is 1.

00:51:30.590 --> 00:51:33.690
l has to be one less
than n or smaller.

00:51:33.690 --> 00:51:35.780
And if n is 1, l has to be 0.

00:51:35.780 --> 00:51:38.030
It can't be any smaller
than 0, so it's 0.

00:51:38.030 --> 00:51:40.530
There's just a one state,
with degeneracy 2, 0

00:51:40.530 --> 00:51:42.850
plus 1, which is 1.

00:51:42.850 --> 00:51:43.760
OK so that's fine.

00:51:43.760 --> 00:51:46.400
It just changes the ground
state by some amount.

00:51:46.400 --> 00:51:48.380
Let's consider the
second excited level.

00:51:48.380 --> 00:51:50.741
So in the second excited
level, we have the states--

00:51:50.741 --> 00:51:52.490
and let me name this
slightly differently,

00:51:52.490 --> 00:51:54.170
so this has energy minus E0.

00:51:54.170 --> 00:52:00.490
The ground state had l
equals 0, and m equals 0.

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:02.370
It had to.

00:52:02.370 --> 00:52:04.770
For the second excited
state, n equals 2,

00:52:04.770 --> 00:52:08.180
how many states are there?

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:12.470
2 squared is 4, so there are
four states, two, three, four.

00:52:12.470 --> 00:52:14.640
And what are their
values of l and m?

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:18.660
Well, if n is 2, l
can be either 0 or 1.

00:52:18.660 --> 00:52:20.650
If it's 0, then m has to be 0.

00:52:20.650 --> 00:52:23.455
If it's 1, m could be
1, or it could be 0,

00:52:23.455 --> 00:52:27.170
or it could be minus 1.

00:52:27.170 --> 00:52:29.700
So this, again, is lm, lm, lm.

00:52:29.700 --> 00:52:33.280
So those are the four states
with energy E2 in the hydrogen

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:33.986
atom.

00:52:33.986 --> 00:52:36.360
And now when we ask, what are
the energies of these three

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:40.320
states, when we include this
so-called fine structure, what

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:41.660
is this going to do?

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:43.940
Well, the ground state is
going to get pushed down

00:52:43.940 --> 00:52:44.600
by some amount.

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:50.290
I should draw this differently
to make it more vivid.

00:52:52.957 --> 00:52:55.415
This gets pushed down by some
amount, with some value of l.

00:52:55.415 --> 00:52:57.330
l here is 0.

00:52:57.330 --> 00:52:59.250
But for these
three states, which

00:52:59.250 --> 00:53:01.420
all have the same
value of little l, 1,

00:53:01.420 --> 00:53:03.360
the denominator is larger.

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:06.260
So the amount by which it
gets pushed down is less.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:08.384
So these three states
get pushed down less,

00:53:08.384 --> 00:53:09.800
but the same amount
as each other.

00:53:13.830 --> 00:53:15.730
That cool?

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:22.350
So these three states--
degeneracy is 3,

00:53:22.350 --> 00:53:24.800
and this state degeneracy is 1.

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:29.410
Now, notice that 1
plus 3 is equal to 4

00:53:29.410 --> 00:53:32.130
is equal to n squared.

00:53:32.130 --> 00:53:37.470
So these states split
into multiplets-- groups

00:53:37.470 --> 00:53:40.135
of states-- which have
to have the same energy

00:53:40.135 --> 00:53:42.214
by rotational invariance.

00:53:42.214 --> 00:53:43.630
If they have l
equas 1, there must

00:53:43.630 --> 00:53:46.260
be three states with the
same energy-- there must be.

00:53:46.260 --> 00:53:49.020
And states with l equals 0,
there's just the one state.

00:53:51.740 --> 00:53:54.520
And if we did the
same thing for E3,

00:53:54.520 --> 00:53:56.560
let's just think about
what would happen.

00:53:56.560 --> 00:53:58.140
So I'm just going
to write the l.

00:53:58.140 --> 00:53:59.431
I'm not going to include the m.

00:53:59.431 --> 00:54:03.940
We have the l equals 0 times 1.

00:54:03.940 --> 00:54:07.500
We have the l equals
1 state, times 3.

00:54:07.500 --> 00:54:09.060
And we have l equals 2 state.

00:54:09.060 --> 00:54:12.180
And how many states are there
in the l equals 2 state?

00:54:12.180 --> 00:54:14.180
Times 5, good.

00:54:14.180 --> 00:54:16.860
And again, this gets
pushed down to some value.

00:54:16.860 --> 00:54:18.360
This gets pushed
down to some value.

00:54:18.360 --> 00:54:20.800
This gets pushed
down to some value,

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:24.012
where this is one,
three, and five.

00:54:24.012 --> 00:54:25.470
And again, these
add up to 9, which

00:54:25.470 --> 00:54:27.180
is 3 squared-- the degeneracy.

00:54:27.180 --> 00:54:29.930
So by turning on the
relativistic corrections,

00:54:29.930 --> 00:54:31.170
we break this degeneracy.

00:54:31.170 --> 00:54:32.170
We lift this degeneracy.

00:54:32.170 --> 00:54:38.104
You break the symmetry,
you lift the degeneracy.

00:54:38.104 --> 00:54:39.520
Now, unfortunately,
this isn't one

00:54:39.520 --> 00:54:41.700
we can control by turning
a dial in the lab.

00:54:41.700 --> 00:54:44.140
No experiment that
I can do in the lab

00:54:44.140 --> 00:54:46.160
will change the value
of the speed of light.

00:54:48.425 --> 00:54:49.925
Well, actually there
are experiments

00:54:49.925 --> 00:54:51.966
that will change the value
of the speed of light.

00:54:51.966 --> 00:54:55.269
If you work in medium, the
effective speed of light

00:54:55.269 --> 00:54:55.810
is different.

00:54:55.810 --> 00:54:57.804
So that's going to change
relativistic effects.

00:54:57.804 --> 00:54:58.720
So that's interesting.

00:54:58.720 --> 00:55:01.178
That tells you that you can
actually vary this continuously

00:55:01.178 --> 00:55:04.220
if you can vary continuously
the index of refraction

00:55:04.220 --> 00:55:06.569
of the ambient system.

00:55:06.569 --> 00:55:08.610
I invite you to think
about how you might do that

00:55:08.610 --> 00:55:10.925
experimentally, because
it's a fun question.

00:55:13.940 --> 00:55:16.150
OK, however, what
I'd really like

00:55:16.150 --> 00:55:19.660
is something where
Professor Evan in his lab

00:55:19.660 --> 00:55:26.730
can actually turn a dial,
and change the spectrum

00:55:26.730 --> 00:55:28.870
in a way that explicitly
breaks the symmetry.

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:30.350
Meanwhile, I also
want an example

00:55:30.350 --> 00:55:32.570
that breaks the
rotational invariance.

00:55:32.570 --> 00:55:34.910
I want to break the 2l
plus 1 states up into 2l

00:55:34.910 --> 00:55:36.550
plus 1 states with
different energies.

00:55:36.550 --> 00:55:38.876
I want to make them
depend on the angular

00:55:38.876 --> 00:55:40.000
momentum in some direction.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:42.095
What must I do in order
to lift that degeneracy?

00:55:47.670 --> 00:55:49.120
AUDIENCE: Add a magnetic field.

00:55:49.120 --> 00:55:49.510
PROFESSOR: Fantastic.

00:55:49.510 --> 00:55:51.200
If you add a magnetic
field, why is that

00:55:51.200 --> 00:55:52.449
going to break the degeneracy?

00:55:56.194 --> 00:55:57.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:02.255 --> 00:56:03.630
PROFESSOR: Give
me an answer that

00:56:03.630 --> 00:56:05.610
depends, not on your
knowledge of chemistry,

00:56:05.610 --> 00:56:09.860
but give me an answer that
depends on symmetries.

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:11.342
Why doe turning on
a magnetic field

00:56:11.342 --> 00:56:13.800
have the potential to split
the degeneracy of the 2l plus 1

00:56:13.800 --> 00:56:14.120
states?

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:15.840
AUDIENCE: You don't have
rotational symmetry.

00:56:15.840 --> 00:56:16.830
PROFESSOR: Thank you, exactly.

00:56:16.830 --> 00:56:18.680
You have no rotational
symmetry, exactly.

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:19.760
So that's pretty good.

00:56:19.760 --> 00:56:29.330
So let's break the 2l plus 1 by
breaking rotational symmetry.

00:56:29.330 --> 00:56:32.672
There are many ways we could
break rotational symmetry.

00:56:32.672 --> 00:56:34.130
We could turn on
an electric field.

00:56:34.130 --> 00:56:35.910
We could turn on
a magnetic field.

00:56:35.910 --> 00:56:39.597
We could put a
shovel in the room.

00:56:39.597 --> 00:56:41.930
But anything that breaks
rotational symmetry will do it,

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:44.250
but a very convenient way is
to do it with a magnetic field.

00:56:44.250 --> 00:56:45.958
Magnetic field is
particularly beautiful.

00:56:45.958 --> 00:56:50.060
So this is effect is now
call the Zeeman effect.

00:56:50.060 --> 00:56:54.190
I believe it was
Faraday-- one of

00:56:54.190 --> 00:56:59.580
the classic electromagnetists
of the 19th century attempted

00:56:59.580 --> 00:57:02.770
to look at the spectral
lines coming off glowing gas,

00:57:02.770 --> 00:57:04.790
and see if they
changed by turning

00:57:04.790 --> 00:57:06.407
on an electric or
a magnetic field.

00:57:06.407 --> 00:57:07.990
It turns out to be
a tricky experiment

00:57:07.990 --> 00:57:10.130
to do, because you need to
have a very well-controlled

00:57:10.130 --> 00:57:11.380
magnetic field,
otherwise what you

00:57:11.380 --> 00:57:12.790
get is just a bunch of schmutz.

00:57:12.790 --> 00:57:15.380
So to get a clean
spectrum, you have

00:57:15.380 --> 00:57:18.550
to have a very uniform magnetic
field, which is not trivial.

00:57:18.550 --> 00:57:19.800
It has to be time independent.

00:57:19.800 --> 00:57:23.477
So Zeeman, at the very end of
the 19th century-- in fact,

00:57:23.477 --> 00:57:25.310
this experiment was
done, I believe, in '96.

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:32.170
So I think the paper
came out in '97

00:57:32.170 --> 00:57:34.455
but the experiment
was done in '96.

00:57:34.455 --> 00:57:35.580
Zeeman did this experiment.

00:57:35.580 --> 00:57:37.210
He said look, if i turn
on a magnetic field

00:57:37.210 --> 00:57:39.418
next to a hot, glowing gas
and look the spectrum that

00:57:39.418 --> 00:57:43.060
comes off, anything
happen to it?

00:57:43.060 --> 00:57:46.931
Why would you think that
anything might happen?

00:57:46.931 --> 00:57:48.930
And the answer to this
one is really quite nice.

00:57:48.930 --> 00:57:51.130
Look, if we compute
the energy, the energy

00:57:51.130 --> 00:57:53.710
is going to be
equal to the Coulomb

00:57:53.710 --> 00:57:57.030
energy plus a correction,
which is the following--

00:57:57.030 --> 00:58:00.540
if you think of the atom
as an electron that carries

00:58:00.540 --> 00:58:03.599
some angular momentum in
the presence of a proton,

00:58:03.599 --> 00:58:06.140
if you think of the electron as
a thing carrying some angular

00:58:06.140 --> 00:58:07.681
momentum, and a
thing with a charge--

00:58:07.681 --> 00:58:09.940
it has a charge and
angular momentum.

00:58:09.940 --> 00:58:12.100
It's going to have
magnetic moment, mu.

00:58:12.100 --> 00:58:13.800
And the magnetic
moment is going to be

00:58:13.800 --> 00:58:21.000
equal to the current of the
charge times the area swept out

00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:24.220
divided by c, because we
work with sensible units.

00:58:24.220 --> 00:58:36.750
And this is equal to minus--
for the case of the atom--

00:58:36.750 --> 00:58:41.180
minus mu, the magnetic
moment of the system

00:58:41.180 --> 00:58:43.920
dotted into the magnetic
field that you turn on

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:44.670
in the background.

00:58:44.670 --> 00:58:46.420
So this is a background
magnetic field.

00:58:46.420 --> 00:58:48.049
I am turning on an
electromagnet, which

00:58:48.049 --> 00:58:50.090
induces a magnetic field
in some known direction,

00:58:50.090 --> 00:58:51.670
with some known magnitude.

00:58:51.670 --> 00:58:53.630
So my dial is the
magnitude of that B field.

00:58:53.630 --> 00:58:55.920
I could make it large,
or I could make it small.

00:58:55.920 --> 00:58:58.010
And it's in a known direction.

00:58:58.010 --> 00:59:02.034
And the point is, our electron
because it's orbiting,

00:59:02.034 --> 00:59:03.700
because it carries
some angular momentum

00:59:03.700 --> 00:59:06.506
and it carries some in charge,
has some magnetic moment.

00:59:06.506 --> 00:59:08.130
So it behaves like
a little bar magnet.

00:59:08.130 --> 00:59:10.200
And that bar magnet wants to
anti-align with the background

00:59:10.200 --> 00:59:11.800
magnetic field that
I've turned on.

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:14.550
So there's an energy penalty
to not being aligned.

00:59:14.550 --> 00:59:21.550
This is the usual dipole-dipole
potential from electrostatics.

00:59:21.550 --> 00:59:29.160
OK and mu here is equal to minus
E over 2mc-- angular momentum.

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:36.370
So this can be computed from
a simple model of the atom.

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:40.930
Whatever, it's easy to compute.

00:59:40.930 --> 00:59:44.201
So this is slightly
annoying, because if E

00:59:44.201 --> 00:59:46.700
is in some arbitrary direction,
let's just simplify our life

00:59:46.700 --> 00:59:50.392
and say that's equal to
E Coulomb minus mu B.

00:59:50.392 --> 00:59:52.350
And I want to turn on a
magnetic field of known

00:59:52.350 --> 00:59:53.650
amplitude in a known direction.

00:59:53.650 --> 00:59:54.899
Let's call it the z direction.

00:59:54.899 --> 00:59:57.480
So this is mu z.

00:59:57.480 --> 01:00:03.040
But this mu z, that's just mu
z is lz times minus E over 2mc.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:09.190
So this is going to
be plus E over 2mc,

01:00:09.190 --> 01:00:11.874
Bz-- I'm going to put
this all together, Bz Lz.

01:00:16.440 --> 01:00:18.321
Everyone cool with that?

01:00:18.321 --> 01:00:19.820
So where this is
coming from, again,

01:00:19.820 --> 01:00:23.000
is just the angular momentum
is telling you the velocity.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.380
The velocity is telling
you the current.

01:00:25.380 --> 01:00:27.790
And then the area is the radius.

01:00:27.790 --> 01:00:33.581
So that's what's giving you
the radius and the angular

01:00:33.581 --> 01:00:34.080
momentum.

01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:39.907
So this is our energy.

01:00:39.907 --> 01:00:42.115
What does this tell you
about the energy eigenvalues?

01:00:45.340 --> 01:00:47.340
They depend on m, right?

01:00:47.340 --> 01:00:49.250
And do we have to solve
the energy eigenvalue

01:00:49.250 --> 01:00:51.080
equation again?

01:00:51.080 --> 01:00:54.060
No, because our energy
eigenfunctions of Ec

01:00:54.060 --> 01:00:55.950
are proportional to
ylm, so they're already

01:00:55.950 --> 01:00:59.300
eigenfunctions of lz.

01:00:59.300 --> 01:01:03.050
So when I take this beast, and
I act on the wave functions

01:01:03.050 --> 01:01:08.440
I erased, but on the 1 upon
little r, capital R, sub nl, y

01:01:08.440 --> 01:01:10.810
sub lm-- when I act
on the ylm's, this

01:01:10.810 --> 01:01:14.880
is just going to give
me h bar m, right?

01:01:14.880 --> 01:01:18.877
So this is just a constant when
acting on the Coulomb energy

01:01:18.877 --> 01:01:19.460
eigenfunction.

01:01:19.460 --> 01:01:20.460
So this is a much
easier problem.

01:01:20.460 --> 01:01:22.793
That way, we don't even have
to make any approximations.

01:01:22.793 --> 01:01:29.280
We can just say exactly energy
Zeeman is equal to minus E0

01:01:29.280 --> 01:01:40.960
upon n squared, nlm
plus E h bar upon 2mc,

01:01:40.960 --> 01:01:42.650
Bz-- the background
magnetic field,

01:01:42.650 --> 01:01:47.730
and this is the m of electron
mass-- times little m.

01:01:47.730 --> 01:01:49.720
And I'm going to write
little m sub l, just

01:01:49.720 --> 01:01:56.676
to distinguish little
m sub l from m sub E.

01:01:56.676 --> 01:01:58.050
So when we turn
on the prediction

01:01:58.050 --> 01:02:02.280
here, when we turn on the
magnetic field a la Zeeman,

01:02:02.280 --> 01:02:04.590
our energy levels will
get split according

01:02:04.590 --> 01:02:07.160
to the different values of m.

01:02:07.160 --> 01:02:10.812
Now if instead of working
with the pure Coulomb system,

01:02:10.812 --> 01:02:12.270
if we were in fact
a little clever,

01:02:12.270 --> 01:02:14.490
and we'd already noticed that
there's a fine structure--

01:02:14.490 --> 01:02:15.600
because they already
knew that there

01:02:15.600 --> 01:02:17.100
was a fine structure
at this point--

01:02:17.100 --> 01:02:20.380
they could see the
different spectra

01:02:20.380 --> 01:02:24.936
in lines coming off of hot gas.

01:02:24.936 --> 01:02:26.310
So it's just an
experimental fact

01:02:26.310 --> 01:02:27.893
you can't turn off
the fine structure.

01:02:27.893 --> 01:02:33.507
This is going to be equal
to e nlm of our correction

01:02:33.507 --> 01:02:35.840
to the hydrogen atom, with
the fine structure corrected.

01:02:35.840 --> 01:02:39.670
So the l equals 1 states and
the l equals 0 states are split.

01:02:39.670 --> 01:02:42.967
Let's focus, for example, on E2.

01:02:42.967 --> 01:02:44.550
So these guys have
a different energy.

01:02:44.550 --> 01:02:46.341
The l equals 1 guys
have a different energy

01:02:46.341 --> 01:02:47.970
than the l equals 0 guys.

01:02:47.970 --> 01:02:49.990
What does this predict
is going to happen

01:02:49.990 --> 01:02:52.240
if I look at my spectral line?

01:02:52.240 --> 01:02:54.930
So what this predicts
is the following--

01:02:54.930 --> 01:02:57.630
it says that if you
have some spectrum that

01:02:57.630 --> 01:03:08.660
looks like this-- so this is
as a function of wavelength

01:03:08.660 --> 01:03:12.650
and i'm looking literally
at what comes off a prism.

01:03:12.650 --> 01:03:14.050
I'm looking at spectrum lines.

01:03:14.050 --> 01:03:15.740
And I'll have a line here.

01:03:15.740 --> 01:03:17.900
And these are going to
be the l equals 0 states.

01:03:17.900 --> 01:03:20.770
This is n equals 2.

01:03:20.770 --> 01:03:22.860
And then there's the
l equals 1 states.

01:03:22.860 --> 01:03:25.820
This is with zero magnetic
field-- Bz equals 0.

01:03:29.820 --> 01:03:38.040
If we turn on a magnetic
field, Bz not equal to zero,

01:03:38.040 --> 01:03:39.720
what should we see?

01:03:39.720 --> 01:03:43.140
Well, what happens
to this state?

01:03:43.140 --> 01:03:46.610
Nothing-- it's the same thing,
because the m is strictly 0,

01:03:46.610 --> 01:03:48.050
so it's the same value.

01:03:48.050 --> 01:03:50.850
And this guy, what
happens to it?

01:03:50.850 --> 01:03:53.242
The m equals 0
state is the same.

01:03:53.242 --> 01:03:54.950
But then it breaks
up-- as everyone said,

01:03:54.950 --> 01:03:57.555
it breaks up into three lines
that are equally spaced.

01:04:01.260 --> 01:04:03.710
It breaks up into three
lines, because one of them

01:04:03.710 --> 01:04:06.750
has m which is plus 1, one
of them has m which is 0,

01:04:06.750 --> 01:04:08.540
and one is m is minus 1.

01:04:08.540 --> 01:04:10.770
So energies will
increase or decrease.

01:04:10.770 --> 01:04:14.170
Let's say this is frequency.

01:04:14.170 --> 01:04:15.290
So we get this splitting.

01:04:15.290 --> 01:04:18.460
And another way to draw
this is as a function of B,

01:04:18.460 --> 01:04:21.570
let's draw the energy levels.

01:04:21.570 --> 01:04:22.680
So there's the 1.

01:04:22.680 --> 01:04:24.150
There's the 0.

01:04:24.150 --> 01:04:25.960
And this stays constant.

01:04:25.960 --> 01:04:30.035
And these guys-- one is
constant, one increases,

01:04:30.035 --> 01:04:30.785
and one decreases.

01:04:34.006 --> 01:04:36.130
When you start getting into
strong magnetic fields,

01:04:36.130 --> 01:04:38.025
weird things happen,
like these guys cross,

01:04:38.025 --> 01:04:40.930
and all sorts of subtle
things can happen.

01:04:40.930 --> 01:04:42.930
But let's ignore the
strong magnetic field case,

01:04:42.930 --> 01:04:44.010
and just focus on this.

01:04:44.010 --> 01:04:46.290
So we see that these guys split.

01:04:46.290 --> 01:04:51.690
So this is what the Schrodinger
theory, or the full story

01:04:51.690 --> 01:04:54.000
would predict-- it came
a little bit after this,

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:57.097
but this experiment
was done in '96,

01:04:57.097 --> 01:04:59.680
so there's actually kind of an
entertaining story about people

01:04:59.680 --> 01:05:01.560
trying to explain this
effect classically.

01:05:01.560 --> 01:05:03.010
Well, look you could
have some angular

01:05:03.010 --> 01:05:04.445
momentum in the z
direction, some angular

01:05:04.445 --> 01:05:06.030
momentum in the x direction,
some angular momentum in the y

01:05:06.030 --> 01:05:06.810
direction.

01:05:06.810 --> 01:05:09.018
The part that has angular
momentum in the x direction

01:05:09.018 --> 01:05:11.170
doesn't do anything,
or in the z direction.

01:05:11.170 --> 01:05:12.795
The part with the x
and part with the y

01:05:12.795 --> 01:05:13.982
can have different polars.

01:05:13.982 --> 01:05:15.690
There's a whole
classical song and dance.

01:05:15.690 --> 01:05:16.290
It's crazy.

01:05:16.290 --> 01:05:17.230
It doesn't make any sense.

01:05:17.230 --> 01:05:18.980
But that's because they were
trying to classical mechanics

01:05:18.980 --> 01:05:20.840
to do quantum mechanics,
which doesn't work.

01:05:20.840 --> 01:05:22.180
So I'm not even going
to bother explaining

01:05:22.180 --> 01:05:23.180
what they were thinking.

01:05:23.180 --> 01:05:26.660
But anyway, so people came up
with a sort of classical crutch

01:05:26.660 --> 01:05:29.720
to say, well that's
not totally insane.

01:05:29.720 --> 01:05:31.870
So this is what Zeeman
got, for example,

01:05:31.870 --> 01:05:33.840
by looking at hydrogen.

01:05:33.840 --> 01:05:37.550
But he did more than
just look at hydrogen.

01:05:37.550 --> 01:05:40.385
I can't remember exactly-- I
think he did it with sodium.

01:05:40.385 --> 01:05:42.010
Matt, do you remember?

01:05:42.010 --> 01:05:44.280
I think he did sodium and iron.

01:05:44.280 --> 01:05:45.755
But anyway, here's
the funny thing

01:05:45.755 --> 01:05:47.130
that he got with
sodium and iron.

01:05:47.130 --> 01:05:48.546
So this is a
different experiment.

01:05:48.546 --> 01:05:50.060
It's exactly the
same set up, but he

01:05:50.060 --> 01:05:52.030
was looking at spectral
lines in sodium.

01:05:52.030 --> 01:05:55.130
And spectral lines in sodium
did a very similar thing.

01:05:55.130 --> 01:05:57.450
There were some
where 1 went to 1.

01:06:01.400 --> 01:06:04.520
And there were
others where 1 went

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:08.546
to-- why did we have three here?

01:06:08.546 --> 01:06:10.920
Just as quick reminder, why
do we have three states here?

01:06:10.920 --> 01:06:12.200
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:14.840
PROFESSOR: Because we have
three states for l equals 1.

01:06:14.840 --> 01:06:25.600
This one state went to one,
two, three, four states,

01:06:25.600 --> 01:06:27.734
with none of them in the middle.

01:06:27.734 --> 01:06:29.150
And in fact, it's
worse than that,

01:06:29.150 --> 01:06:31.108
because they didn't go
to equally spaced states

01:06:31.108 --> 01:06:31.700
in general.

01:06:31.700 --> 01:06:33.650
In general, they did
something slightly funny.

01:06:33.650 --> 01:06:36.690
And the beautiful plot in
his paper looks like this.

01:06:40.130 --> 01:06:44.410
There are four states, and as
you take the magnetic field

01:06:44.410 --> 01:06:47.230
to 0, these four states
all coalesce exactly

01:06:47.230 --> 01:06:49.064
to this one state.

01:06:49.064 --> 01:06:51.355
So this one line is representing
four different states.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:56.990
And this already included
the fine structure,

01:06:56.990 --> 01:07:00.535
so we know that this is
all a single value of l.

01:07:00.535 --> 01:07:02.035
But that apparently
has four states.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:08.810
That's should worry you.

01:07:08.810 --> 01:07:12.926
What does that tell you about l?

01:07:12.926 --> 01:07:14.550
What does l have to
be in order to have

01:07:14.550 --> 01:07:16.444
four states in your tower?

01:07:16.444 --> 01:07:17.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:19.600
PROFESSOR: Half integer--
in particular, what value?

01:07:19.600 --> 01:07:22.830
3/2, crap.

01:07:22.830 --> 01:07:24.790
We already know that
these wave functions

01:07:24.790 --> 01:07:27.090
are described by
the ylm's, right?

01:07:27.090 --> 01:07:28.600
We solved that problem.

01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:29.870
We explicitly solved it.

01:07:29.870 --> 01:07:30.920
Here's the exact answer.

01:07:30.920 --> 01:07:33.246
It's the ylm's.

01:07:33.246 --> 01:07:34.620
But we've observed
experimentally

01:07:34.620 --> 01:07:36.210
that l has to be 3/2.

01:07:36.210 --> 01:07:40.347
But if l is 3/2,
ylm is equal to 0,

01:07:40.347 --> 01:07:41.805
because it's equal
to minus itself.

01:07:45.070 --> 01:07:46.400
This is bad.

01:07:46.400 --> 01:07:47.860
This is 0.

01:07:47.860 --> 01:07:49.840
So this effect is called
the Zeeman effect,

01:07:49.840 --> 01:07:52.743
and this effect is called
the anomalous Zeeman effect.

01:07:52.743 --> 01:07:53.630
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:53.630 --> 01:07:55.300
Which is strange
for two reasons.

01:07:55.300 --> 01:07:57.258
The first reason it's
strange is they showed up

01:07:57.258 --> 01:07:58.312
in the same paper.

01:07:58.312 --> 01:08:00.770
And the second thing is, OK,
you call it the Zeeman effect,

01:08:00.770 --> 01:08:03.110
because there's some
guy named Zeeman.

01:08:03.110 --> 01:08:06.009
Is there some guy
named Anomalous Zeeman?

01:08:06.009 --> 01:08:07.050
It's a very strange name.

01:08:07.050 --> 01:08:09.299
Anyway so this was called
the anomalous Zeeman effect,

01:08:09.299 --> 01:08:12.230
despite appearing in the same
paper, because it's weird.

01:08:12.230 --> 01:08:14.087
It was deeply
disconcerting to people.

01:08:14.087 --> 01:08:15.670
We now just call it
the Zeeman effect,

01:08:15.670 --> 01:08:17.964
but we have the bad habit--
for entertainment value--

01:08:17.964 --> 01:08:20.297
of referring to it still as
the anamolous Zeeman effect.

01:08:20.297 --> 01:08:23.292
I'm not the only one
responsible for that bad habit.

01:08:23.292 --> 01:08:25.750
I'm going to point out that at
the end of this paper-- it's

01:08:25.750 --> 01:08:27.500
a totally awesome
paper, by the way-- it's

01:08:27.500 --> 01:08:29.600
very readable and short--
he says-- I was looking

01:08:29.600 --> 01:08:33.399
at it last night-- it
says, quote possibly

01:08:33.399 --> 01:08:36.580
the observed phenomenon
will be regarded

01:08:36.580 --> 01:08:39.810
as nothing of any consequence.

01:08:39.810 --> 01:08:44.029
OK, so a few years later,
Pauli says the following--

01:08:44.029 --> 01:08:46.319
so Pauli says this,
actually, and this is also

01:08:46.319 --> 01:08:51.410
totally lovely in Science
from 1946 Pauli was in the US

01:08:51.410 --> 01:08:52.170
during the war.

01:08:52.170 --> 01:08:54.674
After the war, he was at the
Institute for Advanced Study.

01:08:54.674 --> 01:08:57.090
At the Institute for Advanced
Studies, while he was there,

01:08:57.090 --> 01:08:58.439
he got the Nobel Prize.

01:08:58.439 --> 01:09:00.744
And he gave-- for the
exclusion principle, which

01:09:00.744 --> 01:09:02.910
we are about to get to--
and he gave a little spiel,

01:09:02.910 --> 01:09:06.310
and it's written up in
this edition of Science.

01:09:06.310 --> 01:09:09.040
And he says, quote,
a colleague who

01:09:09.040 --> 01:09:11.080
met me strolling
rather aimlessly

01:09:11.080 --> 01:09:13.000
in the beautiful
streets of Copenhagen

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:19.010
said to me in a friendly
manner, "You look very unhappy."

01:09:19.010 --> 01:09:22.910
Whereupon, I responded fiercely,
"How can one look happy

01:09:22.910 --> 01:09:25.686
when he is thinking about
the anamolous Zeeman effect?"

01:09:25.686 --> 01:09:32.500
[LAUGHTER]

01:09:32.500 --> 01:09:33.830
So this troubled people.

01:09:33.830 --> 01:09:34.374
Yeah.

01:09:34.374 --> 01:09:35.290
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:09:42.220 --> 01:09:44.389
PROFESSOR: Yeah he found
all sorts of crazy states.

01:09:44.389 --> 01:09:45.680
So this isn't the only example.

01:09:45.680 --> 01:09:47.388
It's just the only
one I'm going to draw.

01:09:47.388 --> 01:09:49.479
But indeed, you can
find five half states

01:09:49.479 --> 01:09:50.967
you can find states with six.

01:09:50.967 --> 01:09:52.050
AUDIENCE: Why [INAUDIBLE]?

01:09:56.787 --> 01:09:58.620
PROFESSOR: Oh, I didn't
draw all the states.

01:09:58.620 --> 01:10:01.078
The spectrum is complicated
and messy, because it's sodium.

01:10:01.078 --> 01:10:02.970
And so there's
all sorts of crap.

01:10:02.970 --> 01:10:04.570
So I'm just not drawing it.

01:10:04.570 --> 01:10:08.370
I'm just focusing on a
specific set of spectral lines.

01:10:08.370 --> 01:10:16.310
Maybe the best way
to draw that is-- OK.

01:10:16.310 --> 01:10:20.540
So this was really troubling.

01:10:20.540 --> 01:10:24.679
So let's put this on
pause for the moment,

01:10:24.679 --> 01:10:26.470
and we'll come back to
it in just a second.

01:10:26.470 --> 01:10:28.010
So meanwhile, there's
something else

01:10:28.010 --> 01:10:29.760
that's sort of annoying
about this system.

01:10:29.760 --> 01:10:34.097
We've got the Coulomb potential,
and the Coulomb potential

01:10:34.097 --> 01:10:35.680
has the following
beautiful property--

01:10:35.680 --> 01:10:41.710
the degeneracy of any energy
state is equal to n squared.

01:10:41.710 --> 01:10:44.410
Meanwhile, various
people were fond

01:10:44.410 --> 01:10:49.550
of observing the fact that
the number of states, which

01:10:49.550 --> 01:10:51.080
I will-- in an
abuse of language--

01:10:51.080 --> 01:10:56.080
call the degeneracy of the
level n in the periodic table,

01:10:56.080 --> 01:10:58.770
is equal to-- well, the
first one there's two.

01:10:58.770 --> 01:11:01.736
And then there's eight,
and then there's 18.

01:11:05.930 --> 01:11:13.180
So two, 8, 8, 18, that's
almost 2n squared.

01:11:15.720 --> 01:11:20.040
Two four 8, 9, 18.

01:11:20.040 --> 01:11:21.870
Cool, maybe there's a
relationship, right?

01:11:21.870 --> 01:11:23.245
And meanwhile,
it's very tempting

01:11:23.245 --> 01:11:25.244
to think there's a
relationship, because imagine

01:11:25.244 --> 01:11:27.012
you have four electrons.

01:11:27.012 --> 01:11:28.970
If you have four electrons,
what you do you do?

01:11:28.970 --> 01:11:30.820
Well, you put an
electron here, and then

01:11:30.820 --> 01:11:32.730
you could put an
electron here, or you

01:11:32.730 --> 01:11:34.357
could put an other
electron here.

01:11:34.357 --> 01:11:36.440
You could also put another
electron here and here.

01:11:36.440 --> 01:11:38.356
Or you could put them
in any combination-- two

01:11:38.356 --> 01:11:40.410
here, put two here,
two here, one,

01:11:40.410 --> 01:11:42.450
one-- you could do all
sorts of stuff, right?

01:11:42.450 --> 01:11:45.990
But if, for the
moment, you imagine

01:11:45.990 --> 01:11:47.722
that electrons have
this funny property.

01:11:47.722 --> 01:11:49.180
Imagine for a moment
that electrons

01:11:49.180 --> 01:11:51.430
have the property that they
can't be in the same state

01:11:51.430 --> 01:11:52.315
at once.

01:11:52.315 --> 01:11:54.440
Then if you have four
electrons-- I don't know why.

01:11:54.440 --> 01:11:55.130
I'm desperate.

01:11:55.130 --> 01:11:56.490
I'm thinking about the
anamolous Zeeman effect,

01:11:56.490 --> 01:11:57.040
among other things.

01:11:57.040 --> 01:11:58.206
I have nothing better to do.

01:11:58.206 --> 01:12:00.560
So just for fun, let's imagine
if I put an elector here,

01:12:00.560 --> 01:12:01.560
I can't put another one.

01:12:01.560 --> 01:12:02.910
So if I have a
two electron atom,

01:12:02.910 --> 01:12:04.360
the second one goes
with one of these.

01:12:04.360 --> 01:12:06.300
A three-electron atom,
a four-electron atom,

01:12:06.300 --> 01:12:07.810
and these guys are all related
to each other, because they

01:12:07.810 --> 01:12:09.212
live in the same
energy level, but they

01:12:09.212 --> 01:12:10.290
have different l
values, so they'll

01:12:10.290 --> 01:12:11.748
have slightly
different properties.

01:12:11.748 --> 01:12:14.950
That suggests that
the one l equals

01:12:14.950 --> 01:12:17.530
0 state should be different
from the 3 l equals 1 states,

01:12:17.530 --> 01:12:18.470
chemically.

01:12:18.470 --> 01:12:21.630
But wait-- there aren't
groupings of one and three.

01:12:21.630 --> 01:12:25.500
They're groupings
of two and six.

01:12:25.500 --> 01:12:32.802
Ah, two-- well, so Pauli
staring at this in 1925

01:12:32.802 --> 01:12:34.260
said the following--
he said, look,

01:12:34.260 --> 01:12:36.180
I'm going to
conjecture two things.

01:12:36.180 --> 01:12:41.000
The first is that
no two electrons

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:48.190
can live in the same state--
inhabit the same quantum state.

01:12:53.170 --> 01:12:55.570
That doesn't give us the
periodic table, though.

01:12:55.570 --> 01:12:58.060
It gives us half
the periodic table.

01:12:58.060 --> 01:13:12.240
There are twice as many states
in hydrogen as you think.

01:13:15.126 --> 01:13:17.000
And you might think that
I'm being facetious,

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:19.315
that he said something a
little more sophisticated.

01:13:19.315 --> 01:13:20.190
But he really didn't.

01:13:20.190 --> 01:13:22.020
What he said is, I
posit of the existence

01:13:22.020 --> 01:13:25.060
of an additional quantum number
which the electron can have,

01:13:25.060 --> 01:13:27.840
which takes one of two values.

01:13:27.840 --> 01:13:30.460
Which translated, says, there
are twice as many states

01:13:30.460 --> 01:13:33.309
as you think.

01:13:33.309 --> 01:13:34.600
So that's exactly what he said.

01:13:34.600 --> 01:13:36.740
So this is called the
Pauli exclusion principle.

01:13:36.740 --> 01:13:40.262
And now this does a
totally spectacular thing--

01:13:40.262 --> 01:13:42.720
and you've probably all seen
this in high school chemistry,

01:13:42.720 --> 01:13:44.370
or even college chemistry.

01:13:44.370 --> 01:13:46.579
Now, first electron goes
here, second electron

01:13:46.579 --> 01:13:48.620
goes here, because there
are twice as many states

01:13:48.620 --> 01:13:50.880
as you think, but then I can't
put another state in there,

01:13:50.880 --> 01:13:52.520
because that's as
many as you can have.

01:13:52.520 --> 01:13:55.690
One can go here, and you
can put up to six in here.

01:13:55.690 --> 01:13:56.340
And that's it.

01:13:56.340 --> 01:14:01.840
So the E2 states, the n squared,
which is 4 times 2 states,

01:14:01.840 --> 01:14:03.940
are somehow related to
each other naturally.

01:14:03.940 --> 01:14:05.920
And this gives you the
structure of the periodic table.

01:14:05.920 --> 01:14:07.336
In fact, an awful
lot of chemistry

01:14:07.336 --> 01:14:08.480
follows directly from this.

01:14:08.480 --> 01:14:10.188
So this is the Pauli
exclusion principle.

01:14:10.188 --> 01:14:12.430
However, it's a little
bit disappointing,

01:14:12.430 --> 01:14:14.980
because while this is
whatever-- some ridiculous rule,

01:14:14.980 --> 01:14:16.354
but we're doing
quantum mechanics

01:14:16.354 --> 01:14:18.800
and they're all
ridiculous rules.

01:14:18.800 --> 01:14:20.730
On the other hand, this
one is just stupid.

01:14:20.730 --> 01:14:21.230
Right?

01:14:21.230 --> 01:14:24.890
This is just, like, look,
it wouldn't it be nice?

01:14:24.890 --> 01:14:31.520
So in '25, a couple guys--
really interesting characters--

01:14:31.520 --> 01:14:37.739
named Goudsmit and Uhlenbeck--
so Uhlenbeck-- wow,

01:14:37.739 --> 01:14:38.780
we're really low on time.

01:14:38.780 --> 01:14:41.100
OK, so I'll just tell
you this, and then I'll

01:14:41.100 --> 01:14:43.320
get to the last of it later.

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:48.310
So Goudsmit and Uhlenbeck--
who were young, kind of naive--

01:14:48.310 --> 01:14:51.310
said, look we've got
two effects here.

01:14:51.310 --> 01:14:54.110
One effect is the
anamolous Zeeman effect,

01:14:54.110 --> 01:14:56.380
and there's this
weird fact that states

01:14:56.380 --> 01:14:58.335
have the wrong total
angular momentum.

01:14:58.335 --> 01:15:00.460
And we have this second
thing, that there are twice

01:15:00.460 --> 01:15:02.250
as many states for
an electron as you

01:15:02.250 --> 01:15:04.410
think in the Coulomb potential.

01:15:04.410 --> 01:15:07.490
How can these two things
fit together naturally?

01:15:07.490 --> 01:15:10.060
Well here's a guess--
suppose that the angular

01:15:10.060 --> 01:15:12.390
momentum that we
calculated when we

01:15:12.390 --> 01:15:17.569
did the estimate of the braking
due to the Zeeman effect,

01:15:17.569 --> 01:15:19.860
suppose that angular momentum
was not the right angular

01:15:19.860 --> 01:15:20.310
momentum.

01:15:20.310 --> 01:15:22.130
Maybe there's more angular
momentum in the system.

01:15:22.130 --> 01:15:23.670
There's angular momentum in
the system from the electron

01:15:23.670 --> 01:15:25.878
orbiting around, but maybe
like a little, tiny Earth,

01:15:25.878 --> 01:15:28.180
the electron itself can
have some intrinsic angular

01:15:28.180 --> 01:15:29.347
momentum.

01:15:29.347 --> 01:15:31.180
It turns out Pauli had
had this idea before.

01:15:31.180 --> 01:15:32.640
In fact, Kramers
had suggested this

01:15:32.640 --> 01:15:35.800
to him, who was a very
young guy at the time.

01:15:35.800 --> 01:15:37.660
And Pauli said, you're
a blithering idiot,

01:15:37.660 --> 01:15:39.490
because if you calculate
how small an electron has

01:15:39.490 --> 01:15:41.410
to be in order to fit all the
other things we know, and you

01:15:41.410 --> 01:15:43.370
figure out how fast it would
have to rotate to explain

01:15:43.370 --> 01:15:44.840
the anamolous Zeeman
effect, the surface

01:15:44.840 --> 01:15:46.990
would have to be moving
faster the speed of light.

01:15:46.990 --> 01:15:48.110
That's ridiculous.

01:15:48.110 --> 01:15:49.630
Leave my office.

01:15:49.630 --> 01:15:58.750
So then Uhlenbeck and Goudsmit--
these two guys-- write a paper,

01:15:58.750 --> 01:15:59.440
and say aha!

01:15:59.440 --> 01:16:01.350
Well, we can explain
this, but let's just not

01:16:01.350 --> 01:16:02.980
assume that the stupid
thing is rotating.

01:16:02.980 --> 01:16:04.810
Let's just say an electron
has some intrinsic angular

01:16:04.810 --> 01:16:05.630
momentum.

01:16:05.630 --> 01:16:07.650
I don't know, why not?

01:16:07.650 --> 01:16:09.400
Electrons have intrinsic
angular momentum,

01:16:09.400 --> 01:16:12.370
and if you assume that electrons
have an intrinsic angular

01:16:12.370 --> 01:16:16.880
momentum-- which I'll call
S for the moment-- so then

01:16:16.880 --> 01:16:18.390
the total angular
momentum, j, is

01:16:18.390 --> 01:16:21.320
equal to l, its orbital
angular momentum,

01:16:21.320 --> 01:16:23.420
plus some intrinsic
angular momentum, which--

01:16:23.420 --> 01:16:25.795
I don't remember what symbol
they used, but we'll call it

01:16:25.795 --> 01:16:28.040
for the moment S-- where
this has the property that S

01:16:28.040 --> 01:16:34.480
squared, for an electron,
sorry, the principle quantum

01:16:34.480 --> 01:16:37.040
number, which I will call
little s is equal to 1/2,

01:16:37.040 --> 01:16:41.214
so m sub s is equal
to plus or minus 1/2.

01:16:41.214 --> 01:16:43.505
So this is like the l equals
1/2 state, but it's not l.

01:16:43.505 --> 01:16:44.546
It's something intrinsic.

01:16:44.546 --> 01:16:46.730
It has nothing to do
with anything rotating.

01:16:46.730 --> 01:16:48.357
It's just a fact
about electrons.

01:16:48.357 --> 01:16:50.190
Suppose electrons have
a little bit of spin.

01:16:50.190 --> 01:16:53.390
Then what you discover is if
you have the l equals 1 state,

01:16:53.390 --> 01:16:55.280
and the electron
has spin 1/2, what's

01:16:55.280 --> 01:16:57.720
the total angular momentum?

01:16:57.720 --> 01:17:00.769
3/2, right?

01:17:00.769 --> 01:17:01.560
So what do you get?

01:17:01.560 --> 01:17:05.755
You get quadruplets, like that.

01:17:05.755 --> 01:17:07.630
So this turns out to
explain-- if you include

01:17:07.630 --> 01:17:09.463
a small relativistic
effect-- this turns out

01:17:09.463 --> 01:17:14.720
to explain the anomalous
Zeeman effect bang on.

01:17:14.720 --> 01:17:16.640
Meanwhile, there
was an experiment

01:17:16.640 --> 01:17:19.210
done in 1922, which is the
Stern-Gerlach experiment,

01:17:19.210 --> 01:17:23.080
in which Stern and Gerlach
discovered that nickel, when

01:17:23.080 --> 01:17:25.315
sent through a magnetic
field gradient,

01:17:25.315 --> 01:17:28.600
bent into one of two
different spots-- never three,

01:17:28.600 --> 01:17:31.110
never zero, always two.

01:17:31.110 --> 01:17:33.040
How can that be?

01:17:33.040 --> 01:17:35.410
Electron spin-- that
wasn't realized until 1929,

01:17:35.410 --> 01:17:37.130
that the connection was there.

01:17:37.130 --> 01:17:41.870
So these guys came up with
this ridiculous postulate.

01:17:41.870 --> 01:17:43.560
This was Uhlenbeck and Goudsmit.

01:17:43.560 --> 01:17:49.460
And let me just quickly--
U-H-L-E-N-B-E-C-K--

01:17:49.460 --> 01:17:51.610
so Uhlenbeck-- amazing,
amazing scientist,

01:17:51.610 --> 01:17:55.390
also the father of the
mathematician Uhlenbeck,

01:17:55.390 --> 01:17:58.140
and she was a total badass,
and has inspired an awful lot

01:17:58.140 --> 01:18:02.259
of physics-- Karen
Uhlenbeck, who's at UT.

01:18:02.259 --> 01:18:04.300
So this is a pretty
interesting and prolific guy.

01:18:04.300 --> 01:18:06.350
But he was also prolific
in the following way--

01:18:06.350 --> 01:18:10.540
he ran a program at the Rad
Lab at MIT during World War II.

01:18:10.540 --> 01:18:12.740
And Goudsmit worked with him.

01:18:12.740 --> 01:18:15.476
And when they were finishing
up, when the war was ending,

01:18:15.476 --> 01:18:17.600
Goudsmit became the scientific
adviser to something

01:18:17.600 --> 01:18:20.140
called Project Alsos.

01:18:20.140 --> 01:18:22.780
Project Alsos was a project
where the military went

01:18:22.780 --> 01:18:25.230
to the conquered
territories in Germany

01:18:25.230 --> 01:18:27.870
to catch the German
atomic scientists,

01:18:27.870 --> 01:18:30.710
and bring them to a
place called Farm Hall

01:18:30.710 --> 01:18:34.190
in England, where they listened
and eavesdropped on them--

01:18:34.190 --> 01:18:37.820
Heisenberg, all the good guys.

01:18:37.820 --> 01:18:40.420
Well, bad guys-- it depends
on-- all the great physicist

01:18:40.420 --> 01:18:42.000
in the German
territory at the time

01:18:42.000 --> 01:18:44.360
were deeply complicated people.

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:45.500
And they listened to them.

01:18:45.500 --> 01:18:47.300
Something called the
Farm Hall Transcripts

01:18:47.300 --> 01:18:49.470
are the transcripts
of those recordings.

01:18:49.470 --> 01:18:52.684
They were written up in a book
called "The Epsilon Project,"

01:18:52.684 --> 01:18:54.350
which is totally
breathtakingly awesome.

01:18:54.350 --> 01:18:57.580
And Goudsmit wrote a
book called "Alsos"

01:18:57.580 --> 01:19:01.240
about this process of hunting
down the German scientists.

01:19:01.240 --> 01:19:07.390
So Goudsmit,
G-O-U-D-S-M-I-T, I think,

01:19:07.390 --> 01:19:09.900
he wrote a book called "Alsos",
which I heartily recommend

01:19:09.900 --> 01:19:12.530
to you, because it's like a
combination adventure story

01:19:12.530 --> 01:19:15.020
and beautiful bit
of physics history.

01:19:15.020 --> 01:19:18.020
So these guys both were at
MIT during the World War.

01:19:18.020 --> 01:19:19.720
So there's a nice
connection here.

01:19:19.720 --> 01:19:21.360
So these guys--
fascinating characters,

01:19:21.360 --> 01:19:23.050
and they came up with this
idea of some intrinsic angular

01:19:23.050 --> 01:19:23.740
momentum.

01:19:23.740 --> 01:19:27.926
Pauli then calls it spin.

01:19:27.926 --> 01:19:28.800
He gives it the name.

01:19:28.800 --> 01:19:32.590
And he develops a
mathematical theory of spin.

01:19:32.590 --> 01:19:34.220
And the mathematical
theory of spin

01:19:34.220 --> 01:19:36.680
will lead to quantum field
theory, relativistic quantum

01:19:36.680 --> 01:19:38.380
mechanics, and will
eventually lead

01:19:38.380 --> 01:19:40.040
to quantum computation,
which is going

01:19:40.040 --> 01:19:42.074
to be the topic of the
last week of our course.

01:19:42.074 --> 01:19:43.490
So what we've done
so far is we've

01:19:43.490 --> 01:19:46.610
explained the discreteness
of atomic spectra,

01:19:46.610 --> 01:19:48.140
and we've explained
the structure

01:19:48.140 --> 01:19:49.422
of the periodic table.

01:19:49.422 --> 01:19:50.880
What we haven't
done, is we haven't

01:19:50.880 --> 01:19:54.200
explained why atoms form
molecules or solids.

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:56.890
And we also haven't explained
what spin is at all.

01:19:56.890 --> 01:19:59.150
Those are the topics in
the next three weeks.

01:19:59.150 --> 01:20:01.110
See you next time.

